Climb up through some easier terrain (~45 ft to this point) and then shoot out left out a leaning, flaring, off-fingers crack to a good stance below a short finger crack in a corner. Muscle your way up this and scramble up some awkward crap to the rails.    Overall, I thought this was a pretty lousy route, but if you've done everything else...

name: Pet Semetary
description: This is a very steep and moderatly "reachy" face climb. It can be more difficult for short climbers. Lead up to the bolt and then  continue up and slightly to the left following good but somewhat widely spaced holds. This is fairly steep at the start, and the difficulty only eases after the first 60 feet. Decent placements for smaller cams exist.

name: Peterman's Route
description: This route combines climbing on good holds and excellent jamming. The pro is extremely good in solid reddish-brown Precambrian Granite. The route simply follows the line of least resistance up the large left facing corner. The final 30' is rather steep but is on great holds. A fun introduction to Fremont Canyon. Many climbers simply lower down to a large ledge at the base of the final steep corner, and this is frequently toproped by beginners and first-time visitors.

name: Peterman's Variation
description: This is a variation to the finish of Peterman's Route. it stays on the face left of the corner and climbs the cracked face to the rim, starting at the ledge some 40' below the top.

name: Raise Your Guts
description: Climb has a couple of weird/ interesting moves mixed in with some good hand jams and finger locks at the top.  Reachy for a 5'10'' guy!

name: Slim Pickins
description: The route folloes a left facing dihedral, by means of a short lieback and then face climbing and stemming. The crux is only a few moves near the start. There are decent holds but pro is sparse. Frequently toproped, along with Mary Ann and Pet Semetary. Possibly the easiest 5.9 in the Bridge Area.

name: Star Plunge
description: Great splitter fingers to a hands corner. 10b staying in the splitter or 9+ if you stem out right.

name: Stone King
description: A good climb, but a little harder to get to. The starting traverse makes the first few placements of gear and belay anchor critical if you lead directly from the Hemateria ledge.

name: Superman
description: Super quality crack on the north side of the bridge.  Fingers and hands, kind of flared, some devious stemming.

name: Wild Flower Arete
description: This is the line shares the start of  Greystoke, moves right and climbs the face to the arete.  There you'll find a bolt that protects the brutal crux move.  Felt hard for the grade. Keep your eye on both sides of the arete as you work your way up.   A couple more bolts and your home free.

name: Working for the Weekend
description: This is a combination crack/face problem, and the climbing seems pretty uniform difficulty with no significant crux. This is a good climb to introduce the area to beginners, since it doesn't require a rappel into the abyss.

name: Droppin Trow for the Bison (5.9)
description: Shoot up right to bolts along crack system. Fingers+hands+good feet=Smile!

name: Local's Favorite, Name Unknown
description: Top half of pitch is a clean, tech-filled hand crack!

name: 5.3 Ramp (unofficial)
description: A nice easy climb great for teaching and learning. Also an easy way to access the anchors for bullet hole if you wish to set up a TR.

name: 5.8-5.9  Wall
description: I decided to lump these four climbs together as I'm not sure of their individual names. However they all go at about 5.8 maybe 5.9 for some. These routes require mantling moves toward the top. These are also great beginner/ warm-up climb as the length between bolts is not much.    According to Steph Newsom: the routes upper wall go 5.9,5.9, 5.7, 5.6, 5.10+, 5.9

name: Bag of Bullets
description: To the right of box of chocolates. Climbs through a tricky roof sequence and then up through the slab. Slab moves are made possible by some pretty juggy bullet holes, hence the route name

name: Bloody Good
description: Ascends a face to a roof with a pancake flake in it.

name: Box of Chocolates
description: A really great climb. Tricky for some to start the route but after that search for the good holds, they're there. Climb over a short bulge to get to a hand crack to clip the third bolt. After the crack the climbing eases off.

name: Bullet holes
description: Bolted in a straight line but this route will require you to move all around the surrounding rock. Some people love this route, others not so much. It's a two cruxer at the third bolt and just  before the anchors which are over a slightly overhung section.

name: Bust a Move
description: There are many variations to starting this climb but most people start just under the overhang there will most likely be a pile of rocks at the base where you can stand to get up on the route.If you are feeling like a real stud you can start this route all the way under the roof and get a really bouldery start.   This route is short but doesn't let up as you climb it.

name: Dish
description: Follow bolts up to a small roof/buldge. This can be avoided to make the route go easier.

name: Last route 5.9
description: Short but fun climb just before the end of the cliff.

name: Lieutenant Dan
description: Another climb i'm not sure of the official name or rating but it looks to go at 5.11 or more. Keep an eye out for an edit.

name: Over Easy
description: Climbs the face right of the overhung Willy hates Marc. Climbs up horizontal cracks to good ledges above. A fun climb and great warm up for the harder climbs to the left.

name: Pretty Hate Machine
description: Climb is located between Twist and Lt. Dan

name: Twist
description: Need more info on the route such as actual name and grade, but it's there!

name: Unknown route 5
description: The crux of this climb is at the third bolt and above.

name: Willi-waw
description: Leads up the an arete, name can be seen under the first bolt.

name: Willy Hates Mark
description: This route has a bouldery start that leads to a nice finger sized crack. Start on pockets under the roof and throw for a decent sized ledge. Once you get past the start the route eases of significantly. This route shares anchors with the 5.9 to its right. If you aren't psyched on boulder problem start it is fun to lower off the other climb to the ledge above the boulder problem and give it a go on TR from there.

name: Zig-Zag
description: Right of Bag of bullets. Climb moves right as you go up to the anchors.

name: Early Grave
description: On the east side,  follow weaknesses and cracks in shale bands leading to a very heady dirt mantle move to a ledge.   From the ledge,  follow the dihedral to the summit,  pulling lightly on blocks at the top.

name: Liar Liar
description: Good corner jam crack with a junky start (worth it).

name: Unknown Crack 1
description: Wide crack with a few chimney moves

name: Main Route - Northwest Face
description: While approaching from the West on the Ridgeline, you'll take the lightly worn trail that leads directly to the base of the wall. The obvious slabby crack runs up and to climbers left. About 70' up you'll see bolted chains as the the first anchor (3 bolts/chains as of August 2017). End of second pitch let's out to a 10' ledge where you can untie and walk to the summit about 100' east.     1 rope needed.

name: South Face Bombay Variation
description: Starts in a flared, bombay squeeze slot formed because the Green River Shale formation eroded out from underneath the red Tower Sandstone.After about 20-30 feet, traverse left into a crack and flake system.If they are still there, Larry and I placed a piton and bolt to use as rappel anchors.  Not safe after 50 years.

name: South Face Direct
description: Start up the rib of red Tower Sandstone which makes it to the ground here.A series of flakes and a short hand crack lead to the top.

name: Ranger
description: corner crack leads to a small roof and then to a finger crack.  Rock quality degrades after roof.

name: Joseph Smith Crack
description: Follow obvious crack up the right (back) side of the first buttress to a nice looking splitter in the roof.  Move left below the splitter to good ledges. Go up and left about 30ft to an old set of anchors.  Pitch two is a short run up the choss, past another set of access anchors, and through an arch.   Hip belay through the arch from a huge ledge.   A short climb up gets you on top and walking off.

name: Gray Metolius? Project/Toprope
description: This toprope is less crimpy than the two lines to the left.

name: McGee Welded Coldshuts project/toprope
description: This climb is not as flat faced as those to the left.  Some pockets, overhangs and corners.

name: Project 2 Chain  Anchors Project/Toprope
description: Flat face steep sustained sandstone climbing with mostly crimpers and some reaches.

name: Red Zone Project/Toprope
description: This project is not completed but is open to anyone. The line can be top roped by rappelling to anchors from wall top. The steep sandstone flat faced wall has many crimp holds and side pulls.  There is a qd in the photo attached to a high bolt.

name: Liquor Chuck
description: Climb the face on the left end of the wall's tuning point into the mouth of the canyon.

name: A Raid on Tripoli
description: This arete route follows an easier line than the arete route to the left but still offers a challenge to stay on the arete line down low.

name: Anne's Route
description: This route is the left most on the wall.  Ascent some ledges to crack and layback system the up and into "V" of gulley.

name: Barret's Privateers
description: This route ascends the arete just right of Delaware.  On a couple of occasions it is possible to chicken-walk off the arete and go for easier climbing but then you don't the get the feeling of being on a narrow arete.  Your goal is stay on the arete line through the final big roof--hands and/or face.

name: Battle of Lexington
description: Ascent the left side of large slab that leans against the main wall. The going gets steeper to a jutting block.  Its been done by going either way around the block.  A long reach gets you home for a few more moves to the rap station.

name: The Benedict Arnold Trail
description: This route goes north to trade for an easier way than the direct.  Crimpy in places and an uncertain handhold needed for the passage through the parallel walls.

name: Cannons of Ticonderoga
description: Cannons begins down and right of the right side of the large slab the lays against the main wall.  From the left side of the flat bench ascent steep rock to the arete and continue up and right to steep rock with ledge like hold.  Finish this section for a short crack or face to ledge and find a way to clip rap bolts

name: Delaware
description: Delaware is the 4th route from the left.  After gaining a ledge on a sandstone corner work across a shaley but firm face of slopers.  Next the formation changes to a short sandstone crack and then unto some ledges for the final holds to the anchors.

name: Federalist   10
description: Next to a bolt you will have to figure out the most perplexing move of all the ten's  moves on this wall while the meter is running.  Some of the foot holds are kind of high.

name: Gaspee Affair
description: A gully route with lot of security.  Sometimes you can just step around the apparent problem and continue towards your goal.

name: King George's Under Prance
description: This route traverses leftward above all of the other routes.  There is one large roof to pass under which is face climbing protected with two roof bolts.  There are rap anchors on both sides.  If you want to use all the anchors (more to the right of the roof) bring some long slings to keep easy flow in the rope belay system.

name: Not Worth a Continental
description: It is easier to begin right of the main line and move up and left on the gray shale stone and make the clip below the roof.

name: Rochambeau Assists
description: The route is quite direct and the obvious roof is fairly negotiable leading to easy going.

name: Sailing to Halifax
description: This fill in route made use of some unused turf between two already existing lines.  Consequently one may want to wander to the right where the going is easier.  The main objective is to pass through the crack roof and then join the route on the right.

name: Siege of Yorktown
description: This class sedimentary route will run you through a variety of handholds textures after you gain access to the top of Forge Rock.  When going left at  the bolt on the major roof as shown in the picture leads to a crack crux.  While going just right of the bolt leads to an almost lunge like stretch to get the good hand ledges under the next roof.  After gaining to the ledge above the 2nd roof their are rap bolt both to the left and to the right.

name: Sunshine Patriot
description: Ascent the gulley marking use of cracks, ledges and face holds.

name: Valley Forge
description: Valley Forge is located on the east face of the Rev Wall and begins immediately to the right and below a projecting block about 12 feet high.  Strenuous moves get hand hold access to the large block (Forge Rock) but doesn't assure getting on top of it.  Continue up the crack a short distance crossing a slippery face to some roof holds.  Pull it down and angle to the left for the anchor bolts.

name: War of 1812
description: Some say it is an 8 while others say it is a nine.  While next to a bolt you have to use a single strong hold, really this is what happens quite often on an eight.

name: Whiskey Rebellion
description: The route passes along a shallow section of crack in the light gray shalestone and later passes left of the biggest roof section but has neither good foot holds or hand holds to make for an easy passage.

name: Zach Cornwallis Surrenders
description: You always on steep turf fighting on this face route of the Rev Wall.  In general big hand holds will get you through.

name: Victor of the Spoils
description: A bolted face climb with a difficult to pass roof low on the line.

name: A Wyoming Pipe Dream
description: Some sidepulls from the left will get you right to easier going.

name: Amateur Hour
description: A face climb on big holds low and then a thin passage into the scant featured white dolomite dihederal.

name: Analog Girl
description: Third route on Alpha Flatiron.

name: Another Parallel Universe
description: The rightmost route on the Beta Flatiron. Steep face with tunnel handhold pockets.

name: Bought in Colorado
description: Some moves on overhanging rock with big hold and small feet and then easier going.

name: Bumper to Bumper with Maybellene
description: Starts steep than lower angle to overhanging dolomite roofs.

name: Casual Match
description: A pleasant face climb for a warm up. shares anchor bolts with rightmost route.

name: Channels for Dopamine
description: climb the slightly bulging inside corner utilizing the intermittent crack and face holds to the right.

name: Done with Drilling Drones
description: A steep face climb with some big holds.

name: Entanglements Outward Bond
description: Proceed up a slightly overhanging inside corner and then left on the steep right face of the Tumbling Corner Formation.

name: Fat Boy Slim Dreams
description: An impressive looking overhanging arete project.

name: Go Right or Get Left
description: Center route on the main headwall of the Beta Flatiron.  From a deep pocket it's your choice go right or get left.

name: Going Zen Sane
description: A roofy dihederal leads to a three face roof then ledges.

name: Gutterman's Staircase
description: A steeply overhanging face with mostly big holds and a roof finish.

name: Inversion Therapy
description: A very strenuous ovehanging start leads to a twenty feet traverse and then onto a 7 feet splitter crack roof.

name: Jacob's Wrungless Ladder
description: A balancy arete climb.

name: Killed by Digital Dryfire
description: A steep face climb on the left side of the Beta Flatiron

name: Modeling Walrus Fashion
description: A steep face route with big holds and near corner exposure.

name: Moses was a Basket Case
description: Sidepulls will get you up this red rock channel way.

name: Not on My Face
description: Center route on Alpha Flatiron.  A sparsity of holds but excellent bolt locations

name: Open Air Theatre
description: An overhanging arete climb with a roof finish.

name: Platte River Bust
description: An overhanging line using horizontal cracks and holds.

name: Polecat  Corner
description: A tricky overhanging start leads up red rock to big holds on steep face then you meet the overhanging and somewhat featureless while dolomite cap.

name: Sudden Death for Rechargeables
description: An overhanging crimpy climb.

name: Sunrise Iron Girl
description: A good warmup climb with big holds and easier option to the right as in "chicken walking."

name: Sweet Betsy from Pike
description: An initially steep face climb leads to low angle moving and the dolomite cap.

name: Time isn't holding Us
description: A flat faced climb on steep rock.

name: Turncoat
description: A hand crack within and next to a dihereral make for gear placement and some hangers at the top are useful for belaying.  Decent:  Walk around.

name: Yow-ze  Yow-zo
description: Mostly side pull climbing until the dolomite head.

name: Belli Dancers Twist
description: Some steep face leads to a left angling horizontal climb and then onto easy face.

name: Cage Fight
description: Get ready to pull out all your moves in this quick prizefight. Some people have even taped their right hand.

name: Chimney Fire
description: Traverse up to the base of the chimney from the right.  Ascend the sport chimney utilizing crack and face climbing skills. Move right along the huge undercling and follow the arete to the anchor.

name: Clams on the Halfshell
description: Climb the red steep face and proceed more at straight up and then left onto the last big clam shell hold and then over the edge to easier face.

name: Controlled Flight
description: File your flight plan with air traffic control by starting 10 feet right of the Maroon Tower base. Gain altitude to reach the major ramp and Barrel Roll left up the major dihedral. Launch left out onto the Maroon Tower and try not to pull a Split S.

name: Cow Foot Trail I
description: A hard start and then move up the overhanging gully using more face climbing than stemming.

name: Crossing the Great Divide
description: Climb the steep red face on the right set of bolts and proceed thru the narrowest location in the horizontal roof clipping a bolt to the right and then traverse left to access to the easier face.

name: D-Cup Love
description: The sustained 68 deg from horizontal wall has a major roof about 1/2 way up which is the eliminator zone.

name: Ecoblast
description: Ecoblast starts in the small alcove adjacent to the long boulder resting 10 feet from the cliff. After climbing up the ramp, continue up the projecting fins, ease through the gray-stained alcove (don't forget to use the no-hands rest), and step left onto the finishing headwall.

name: Ground Control to Major Tom
description: The crux will hit you soon and it is likely that you will take flight.

name: Oregon Trail Romance
description: This overhanging route begins as a face climb and ends with some crack moves if done the securest way.

name: Out of the Wagons
description: A face climb the begins stemming about a crack and then head left and near the top heads right to bolts.

name: Pretzel Me in Country Swing
description: Climb the right set of bolts on the steep red face.  At the roof begin at the narrowest passage using the high bolt on the right on the face above.  Traverse right soon standing up on that ledge and then proceed up the overhanging face to the anchors.

name: Robbing the Russian Kradle
description: Most of the route that lies on the white rock is over hanging.  From a corner face climb to right to  a perch about 10 feet below a roof. Proceed up to and through the roof and up the last of the face.

name: Running on Borrowed Power
description: Start on the bouldery steep face 15 feet right of the Maroon Tower base. On the major ramp traverse right (crossing Stage Fright) and carefully continue up the steep laybacks on the headwall above.

name: She's Got Shape
description: The crux is coming out of the 12    feet face roof and over its edge.

name: Side Trip to Pine Bluff
description: Some difficult moves above the small grotto get one onto the east face of the Maroon Tower.  From here the line stays on the face just left of the left edge deviating to the better holds.

name: The Silver Highway
description: Speed as fast as you want on the Autobahn, clipping silver as you climb just left of the major left-facing dihedral.

name: Stage Fright
description: Start at the base of the dihedral with a perched pillar of rock 15 feet off the ground. Climb past the perched pillar on easy rock, traverse left on the major ramp (crossing Running on Borrowed Power) and carefully continue up the headwall above.

name: Airborne Coffee
description: The route is quite easy from the start until nearing the roof.  The quartzite cap will not allow passage anywhere and anyway but the meter is running.

name: Alcohol Crisis
description: climb thru the crack and ledges using some open handholds to gain the dolomite cap rock face finish.

name: Almost Carefree
description: On this white surface, the holds are few, so glide past them with little concern for the problem is to finish.

name: Augmented Reality
description: A few move of difficult stemming lead to access of the holds on the left face.  The climb get easier until the dolomite cap.

name: Baby Steps for a Lummox
description: A steep but easy route on big holds.

name: Boxer Vision
description: Cross right from a major corner to a mildly overhanging corner and proceed to roof of dolomite. Proceed past the left (4th) bolt.  The extraneous hanger to right is a variation (project) that gets you to the curx of Imperchable.

name: Cinnamon Daemons
description: Just right of the major left facing dihederal of Visiting Red Lodge is an overhanging bulge with some bolt visible on near horizontal skyline.  After surmounting this bulge there are 3 variation thru overhangs leading to the summit of Crest Top Tower.

name: Compact Love Space
description: Face climb to a shallow thin crack dihederal briefly doing one finger jam? Then comes a lot of open palm hand holds.

name: Crossfit  Vudoo Training
description: Big holds at first lead to smaller holds after the midway ledge and then the clip to the anchors requires some negotiating.

name: Cut for the Chase
description: Climb left of the prominent outside corner (whitish)   into the overhanging red rock and up to a corner of the dolmite base and past this bulge.

name: Deep Cuts
description: Work you way up a less featured inside corner to a shallow dihederal and finish crossing right and up on the white dolomite.

name: Diamond "K" Marveling
description: Finding some hidden holds will get one past the steep start easily but hooking the anchor bolts that are on the vertical face of the summit roof can be a game of missing your tag transfer.

name: Dinning on Red Herring
description: Proceed along an offset seam to a cleft roof and upward into a corner.  Steep big hold lead out of the corner.  This route offer some unusual position for resting.

name: Fizzle of Zach Attach
description: Climb the arete leading right onto the face and up left then right to the roof and don't goof getting stood up as this is your proof.

name: Forecasting Mistakes
description: Some steep reachy face holds lead to a right traverse but soon you will be try to figure out how to get out of the upper dihederal.

name: Gleaning Twisted Asymmetry
description: Passing several section of bulges and will get you to easier going on the dolomite cap rock.

name: The Homeless return Foodless
description: Face climb steep strenuous overhanging sections with some long reaches to a most difficult finish on the scanty featured dolomite.

name: Imperchable
description: Some crack climbing and laybacking lead to a awkward perch under a mild overhang for some hand grouping to find the best hold.

name: Neopheete Petee
description: This lone route's face gently sweeps upward and gets steeper to a mild overhang in the capping quartzite rock.

name: Not a "D" Cup In Sight
description: The beginning is steep but with big hold and after a ledge in the middle, one can get to the marbled headwall of smaller handholds sooner than one thinks.  Don't quit thinking as you are clipping the lowering bolt.  Cow Feat Pete did and had to return for an honest summiting.

name: Overstretching the Tale
description: a difficult face start leads to intermittant crack and jug holds but the hard part is passing the dolomite roof.

name: Pull Down Resistor
description: While on this White Wall figure out the moves thru, around or inside the book section and proceed to the projecting dolomite roof.  After standing upon the top ledge of this roof you can clip the anchor bolts.

name: Pursuing the Red Baron
description: This mind focusing route takes a lot of micro adjustments for the feet to set up for the next move.  If you do it too slow you meet the the Red Baron scoring another hit.

name: Red Cloud Gets Wounded Knee
description: Red Cloud gets Wounded Knee is a route of intricate move and balance while trusting you feet. It too has a roof problem going through the quartzite cap.

name: Red Wing Goose
description: Begin in what appears to be a seeming unusable intermittent crack in the corner of some bulges and ledges.  Proceed up and onto the steep dolomite face.

name: Scarbox Trapper
description: A hummocky series of bulges leads to some yellowish dolmite the appears featureless.  Porceed left across this face.

name: Shelf Life
description: Climb in the vicinity of a shallow lip faced crack to a roof with a close out of intermittent crack features to a stance on a shelf.  Next, figure out the exit.

name: Side Cuts
description: An initially steep face climb leading to lower angle dolomite with smaller holds.

name: Turning on Divinity Street
description: Turning on Divinity Street right at the left transition from stained Blanco Wall to red rock wall.  The route begins in dihederal and move up a series of block by often going onto the left arete and finishes on an easier section of the quatzite cap.

name: Valley of Distraction
description: The route proceed up the inside corner stemming and face climbing up to bulbous red rock and finishes near the top the white dolomite cap.

name: Visiting Red Lodge
description: A steep corner with several bulges to move past

name: Wasp Fokkers
description: Wasp Fakers begin in a steep shallow corner and soon accesses the left arete to climb over the face between the two unpromising lines of the left and right cracks.  Next it angles right to gain the crack right of the projected crack of where the route began and continues up this short crack to a big ledge and rap bolts.

name: Woody Pecker
description: the face requires some moving out right and back while passing through the red dolomite and possibly a hand jam to get around the quartzite cap.

name: A Stroll throught Time
description: Doing A Stroll Through Time will cover some Mississippian age limestone with chert crystals for holds, and after you overtake some fossil snails you get to the overhanging corner that is readily stemmed and some big holds to exit to the rap bolts.

name: Ally Ally Oxen Free
description: Ally Ally Oxen Free is the long route on the right slab which is just left of the grotto area. Climb the outside of the slippery low corner and over some blocks to the bottom of the right slab.  On the face some of the holds may be hiding,

name: Auctioneer Barmaid
description: Auctioneer Barmaid has a short steep section and then moves nearer and meets the route to the left.

name: Blue Haired Level Headed Bar Maid
description: Steep face on mostly big holds but with lot rests.

name: bric-a-brac
description: Sort your way through a large group of holds choosing those that match your knickknack needs.  Is the climbing easier to the left of the bolts or follow the bolt line,  maybe right?

name: Confronting Anxiety
description: Confronting Anxiety angles up and right into a shallow crack system but is mostly mostly edges for holds and shares the anchor with the 2 routes to the right.

name: Cow Foot Trail for Sheep Thrills
description: The Cow Foot Trail for Sheep Thrills is the easiest route on Switchbax Wall.  The route ramps up and right over blocks and then to ledges with several re Peats.

name: Cow Foot Trail II
description: Cow Trails II angles up a ramping series of ledges rightward until a flake on the left separates from the wall and one can layback up it to the anchors.

name: Drama for SNAGS
description: Drama for SNAGS first encounters a short section of in your face steep crimp climbing, then travels an easy section of mild mannered moves, but then next tests your manner of interaction with the need for careful countering, and then it off to easy loping.

name: Escher's Stairs
description: Escher Stair is about a dead vertical wall with 3 stair step roofs.  Excellent moves.

name: Field Effect Switch
description: Field Effect Switch requires crossing the threshold of a bulge with poor feet and using holds within lunge reach.  Once on this big hold the route moves right over steep turf and then back left to anchors.

name: Fun Hog
description: Fun Hog is a 90 feet route on the Center Slab. It's upper half is steep with large holds and some arete like moves. The start is the left facing corner but it can be climbed by stemming, crack or face moves to the ledge. Next is a chimney to negotiate and then you are on the long face.

name: Harold is Banging Something
description: Harold is Banging Something is an overhanging route with crack holds and some surprising burly pulls.

name: Hedging
description: Hedging follows a line under a buff colored roof and exits to the right on easier face and then moves left to the low anchors that server the other 4 routes to the left.

name: High Step Transformer
description: High Step Transformer needs some high stepping to transform your location to easier standing than under the bulge.

name: Leaving Stonerville
description: The route moves through the steeper face above the left corner of the ledge and then angles slightly right going "straight" to a mild overhanging head wall where a final bolt protects the traverse upward and to the left to the anchor finish.

name: Mother and Daughter Reunion
description: Mostly steep beautiful face climb above the 2 crack moves with very positive pinches and the rest is tight crimps.

name: Pulling the Trust Plug
description: Pulling the Trust Plug is easy face climbing on both ends with the hard crack up move being passing over the chockstone.

name: Pyramid Power
description: Pyramid Power above the ledge looks more a crack climb for a brief bit but the thin cracks useful lieback lips are brief and the crux is above that deceptive zone.

name: Pyramid Scheme
description: Pyramid Scheme is a sustained difficulty vertical face of crimps and side pulls.

name: Shotgun Love
description: Shotgun Love is a fun line near the left side of the the Center Slab.  The route is not very straight at the bottom because it incorporates the easiest sections in the locale of the upper easy crack and face. Rests are frequent on this line along with big holds.

name: Stand Off
description: A low short steep face with some big holds and some little holds.

name: Unknown 10b/c
description: Follow a shallow slightly overhanging depression in the wall for several bolts before busting left beneath a rooflike feature. Make a couple of hard moves up a shot crack crack left of your last bolt below the roof with big but fairly clean fall potential, then make a short traverse back right to clip a thank god bolt. Finish up overhanging rock to a two bolt anchor.
blocky and insecure

name: Babylon
description: Not so popular but aesthetic

name: Bulls on Parade
description: sequential start leads to a low crux. Either end on TRG's anchor or continue through the next roof at .13?

name: Choss Thumper
description: The last route in the cave? Start right of TRG and pull through some lower quality rock to reach a hard crimp sequence that ends in a big move to a hero jug. A few easier moves lead to a compression crux and some sharp holds before reaching a final hard move right before the final roof. Continue out the roof for 2 more bolts. Stopping at the first set of chains is slightly easier..13-

name: Diamond in the Rough
description: Start right of TRG on some loose rock before gaining the obvious large hueco continue up great moves past 3 bolts before merging with TRG.

name: Don't Believe The Hype
description: Big moves between generally good holds

name: Global Warm Up
description: Steep and juggy

name: The Hype Extension
description: the continuation of Don't Believe the Hype through the next roof with some good movement.

name: Jesus Take the Wheel aka Diamond in the Rough EXT
description: Clip the Draw left of the TRG anchor and continue up the final roof and headwall.

name: Moral Hazard
description: Steep climbing on good holds

name: Paul's Boutique
description: Consistently good movement all the way to the chains. DO IT!

name: Sayanora
description: The Gary Falk Memorial Route. Traverses from TRG all the way into the Hype Extension.    Clip the first 3 bolts on TRG and then head left clipping a draw between TRG and Bulls then continue left through the crux of stinger and eventually into the hype extension.

name: Stinger
description: Fantastic climbing with a stout crux at the roof. Solid at the grade.

name: TRG Teton Rock Gym
description: A bouldery low section gives way to big moves and gymnastic climbing with big holds.

name: Fat Albert
description: Solid rock. Just a fun way to get back up after jumping the cliff.

name: Host Jump
description: On the north side of the northeast boulder, start with both hands on a waist high crimp and throw high to the lip.  It could probably also go statically.

name: Patient Zero
description: Start on the big rail in the middle of the east face of Trinity Boulders.  Reach up to a second, higher rail, and top out.

name: A Thousand Cranes
description: A polished slabby limestone sport route. Fun movement, interesting variety of holds. Contender for the greasiest sport route in Jackson.  Guidebook is out of print, but this climb used to be rated 5.9 until its holds became so polished that was upgraded to 5.10a!

name: Hoist
description: Another fun little route with a devious sequence. Reminiscent of climbing at Blacktail Butte. Interesting, small holds.

name: The Joker
description: Climb featured and somewhat polished limestone on the right side of the face with Thousand Cranes. The climbing is reasonably sustained and has fun movement with some neat pockets and edges. Shares 2-bolt anchor with Thousand Cranes.

name: Petzl Logic
description: No distinct crux on this awesome climb (at least I didn't think so). If you enjoy burning calves and limestone pinching, this one's for you. Nice and sustained.

name: Shady Grove
description: A fun little route. The rock's a bit different than you'd find at the rest of the Shield. Fun patina-like edges and some pockets/horizontals. A good warmup.

name: Above Electric Shower
description: This pitch starts at the Electric Shower anchors halfway up the wall. Either climb the unnamed(5.9 sport) pitch or Electric Shower (5.11b) to get to these anchors. Bring your second up to a fairly comfortable belay and start on up.    Fun edge and flake climbing on sometimes sharp holds will bring you to another bolted anchor near the clifftop.

name: Electric Arch (Mulvado Edge)
description: No real crux to this bad boy, just fun movement. I'm not sure of this route's name, but I've heard it called Electric Arch. I'm also fairly certain Greg Miles established it (he developed Electric Shower's second pitch, which went in around the same time).    Anyway, this pretty much follows the corner and arete of the arch that forms the roof of Electric Shower. Some interesting liebacking and ramp-crawling. Can be a little dirty.

name: Electric Shower
description: An intense route that requires some faith in tiny holds. Technical slab down low, hard roof near the top. A classic of its type.

name: Muff Buster
description: A fun, yet somewhat non-memorable sport route. More slabby edges, pinches, and sidepulls.

name: She's Gotta Have It!
description: A fun climb with a touchy slab face down low and a great roof up high. Unfortunately, the climb continues through a bit of easy, junky rock above the roof. Watch yourself up here.

name: Dengue Fever
description: Easy climbing leads to a high first bolt above a small roof where the route's thin, technical crux is encountered. Above, the thin face climbing keeps you on your toes, literally and figuratively between the modestly spaced bolts. The difficulty gradually eases before the upper roof is encountered. Good climbing and great holds takes you through the roof. Above, thin, slabby face climbing again keeps you on edge until you reach the anchor. Great rock is found throughout this climb.

name: Fandango
description: Follow bolt line past overlaps at 1/3 and 2/3 height with classic low angle technical Shield climbing in between. Near the top pull up and over the larger roof to anchor.

name: Frida's Bone
description: Classic low angle Shield terrain leads to a steep blocky section at halfway. Continue on varied wonderful climbing straight up toward the gigantic roof to find chains that are shared with Georgia's Fly.

name: Georgia's Fly
description: Follow the bolt line that aims for the leftmost and lowest part of the big roof above. Continue up over nice and varying terrain to the big roof before heading up and right to the chains below the roof that are shared with Frida's Bone (10-).  **Former sparsely protected trad route, now with bolts thanks to Greg Miles!

name: The Hunter
description: Follow the vague crack system up past the right end of the steep terrain at half height. Continue straight up past a few more bolts to a more broken section of the huge roof. Pull it up and right to chains shared with Naughty Guides and La Bamba.

name: La Bamba
description: Awesome face climbing down low that's not too hard, yet not too easy. The roof is pure fun!

name: McFlatus Roof
description: Very enjoyable face climbing on great edges (some of them flakes) leads to a large roof. Clip the bolt, feel around, and pull the thing! There's a pin in a horizontal crack right above the lip... clip it if you must, but beware of rope drag. The fall would be fine without clipping the pin.    There's a variation that sports an independent start just left of McFlatus, then joins with it below the roof.

name: McFlatus Roof Variation
description: Climbs moderate terrain for 2 bolts before connecting with the regular McFlatus Roof route. While this variation is listed in the McFlatus Roof route description, I felt like it deserved its own description here because it avoids the hard face crux at the bottom of McFlatus Roof. Instead, the roof at the top of the pitch is the crux. It's a nice way to avoid that hard face move, perhaps making it a better warm-up for those wary of starting out on something crimpy right off the deck.

name: Naughty Guides
description: Another fun 10a. Slightly trickier than its neighbor to the right (La Bamba), yet just as fun. Thin slab just before the roof. Both of these routes are quite polished. Best not to do them in the summer sun.

name: Nhervus Sheep
description: An insanely hard low crux (or so I thought) leads to slightly easier climbing, which then leads to an interesting roof. Technical! Try to catch it in the shade, or you'll be hating life.    Careful moving past the first bolt.

name: P-G-T
description: Two pitch Pownall-Gilkey training route. Left side of the overhang is a hanging left facing mini corner. Climb steep bottom, then traverse right on ledge into "The Bulge' Belay from bolts. Pitch 2: Climb 5.6 slab with small cam protection to bolt anchor, Rap 40 m

name: Bolt Face
description: Fun moves, nice holds, short (but hard) crux section. Hard for the grade, or so I thought.

name: The Bulge
description: Formerly a trad route that follows a crack in a left facing corner, this route sprouted bolts sometime around Fall of 2017. Face climbing on big holds with the occasional jam here and there. Pretty fun and a nice alternative to the typical routes at the Shield.

name: Deception
description: Start up The Bulge crack for ~10 feet before pulling right out onto the face. Continue up the low angle face on insecure moves. A committing move gets you below the steep section and then a few more gets you over the bulge. After pulling through the steeps, continue on past easier climbing and a ledge to the chains that are a bit further up than you think!

name: Drill and Repetition
description: Intriguing climbing that avoids the large roof, but still manages some exciting moves.

name: Hoi Polloi
description: A fun, short slab route with a though-provoking move or two.

name: Hook It
description: Apparently this route has gotten easier with time, as a current guidebook lists it as 5.7. I'll stick with the original guidebook(s) grade of 5.9.   Fun, easy face climbing leads to a large roof which is pulled on titanic jugs. Easier climbing leads to the top. Great moves over the roof!    There is a variation that starts just left of this route and is exponentially harder. I've only done it once, and pulled on a draw to get over the roof.

name: Hot Blubber
description: Thin climbing on kindly spaced bolts! What is really special about this climb is the sense of exposure throughout, as it's bolted on the edge of a huge right-facing roof! Steep start leads to thin low angle Shield climbing. Continue up and right to a tough bulge, then continue up on lower angle terrain to chains that are further up there than you may expect!

name: Jam or Slam
description: Awesome route invoving fun pulls between interesting limestone pods (with the usual mix of Shield slabby face moves). Solid for the grade.

name: Patti's Butt
description: P1 (5.7, 60ft) - Run up to the first bolt, which is about 25 feet off the ground on the right-facing side of the corner just before it gets steep. As it gets steeper there is a second bolt in the steep, blocky section. As the pitch flattens out the easy crack could take a 4 or 5 cam or you can just run it out to the anchor, which is just to the right of a very obvious tree.  P2 (5.7+, 70ft) - Slab climbing above the tree and past a newer sapling that can be slung as quick protection. A smaller cam can be placed too before the first bolt, which is about 20ft above the belay ledge. Five or six draws to the top, which is on a huge dirty platform below the beginning of an obvious right-facing corner. This is some of my favorite moderate slab climbing at The Shield.  At the top of P2 is where this route starts to get a little dirty. Mind your feet here if there are people climbing anything climber's right of you. Also, your belayer might appreciate it.  P3 (5.6, 50ft) - Follow the crack and right-facing dirty corner up and onto some 4th class terrain to an obvious pine wrapped with slings for rappelling. It looks like a lot of it is flaky and barely in there, though its almost all solid...  [UPDATE: a significant amount of rock fell from the P3 corner in the Spring of 2019, ripping the "obvious tree" atop the first pitch from the wall. P3 is still climbable at ~5.6, but different! Rapping from the top of P2 is highly suggested. Everything else seems unchanged, except a pile of debris at the bottom of the route.]  P2 and P3 can easily be combined with a 60m.  Rap to the ground with twin 60s or to the top of P1 with one. 50m WON'T get you there. Then rap P1 with one 60m or w/e.

name: Variation
description: Easy, but enjoyable face climbing bookends one stiff move at the roof (rated V4 in the guides) that involves a big undercling lockoff with a long reach to a good hold. It's easy toprope from either Drill & Repetition and Hook It and it's not an altogether horrible climb, which is the allusion made in the guides. The hard roof move is a fun challenge at the least. The Dramis guide shows this as a variation to Hook It and rated 5.9 V4 but it is fully bolted as an independent line.

name: 8 Second Ride
description: A fun moderate with somewhat spacey bolts. Feels similar to Bulldoggin', but bigger holds & less sustained.     Called 10 Second Ride and given .10c in the old guidebook.

name: Alive in Wyoming
description: Some 5.8 climbing takes you to the roof, where a loooooong reach to a suitcase handle jug allows passage over the roof.  5.9 climbing continues to the anchor.

name: Betty Tendon Blaster
description: The best 5.9 at Rodeo and the usual warmup.  The climb begins with 30 feet of slab, to a fun roof move, and then quality crimping and edging to the anchors.

name: Buck Dancer
description: Cruxiest moves at the bottom and top, with a somewhat burly roof pull at midheight. Fun!

name: Bulldoggin'
description: Three different crux sections keep this climb interesting.  Save some energy for the finish! The first crux is just passing the small roof at the first bolt.  The next crux comes at midheight and involves thin, but positive crimps.  The final crux is just past the last bolt and is a difficult sequence of moves on sloping pockets.  The finishing moves make this climb a challenging onsite for the grade.

name: Copenhagen
description: One of the better climbs at Rodeo.  A bouldery move off the ground gets you into 30 feet of slab climbing.  A difficult move over a roof leads to balancy moves to the next bolt.  Don't fall here!  Slightly spaced bolts up the headwall above get you to the anchor.

name: Cowgirls Wear Chaps Only
description: Start up "8 Second Ride" for two bolts before cutting right up a line of rust-colored bolts, which were reinstalled by Greg Miles in 2016.

name: I Against I
description: Entertaining face climbing above the roof is the highlight of this route.  The climb begins with 30 feet of slab to the standard Rodeo roof move.  The final headwall to the anchors is thin and thought provoking.  Stay left of the upper bolts for the easiest passage.

name: Louise
description: Shallow pockets, sloping holds, and moving left/right of bolts characterize this one. Fun and different holds than most of its Rodeo counterparts.

name: Middle Route
description: It starts on dirty low angle terrain before arriving at a large section of the roof. Pull over the roof on small, non-patina holds, continue up and right over the overlap, before meeting up with the upper few bolts of Redman.  This route is still bolted in a more old-school fashion. Just a heads up.

name: Quickdraw McGraw
description: Fun climb characterized by vertical pockets at the powerful roof. A fairly long (but easy) run to the anchor from the last bolt. Rated .10a in the old Sotille guidebook. The roof is a fair bit burlier than that (I thought).

name: Redman
description: Cruxy near the roof pull. In a sea of those great Rodeo patina edges, sometimes it's hard to see the often fundamental hidden pockets. Fun edge pulling above roof.

name: Rodeo Queen
description: Intriguing movement on some strange holds. Probably my least favorite route here (although I've heard "Middle Route" is pretty bad too).

name: Thelma
description: Quite fun edges similar to those on Betty Tendonblaster, but not quite as good! Rated .10a in the old guidebook, it's just not that hard.

name: Destination Unknown
description: Route "C" in the photo, this climb is between the arete and Walking in L.A. Short people will be vertically challenged!

name: Hustler
description: AN excellent climb requiring hard overhanging pulls and delicate footwork. The route ascends the arete and face at the far right side of the north face. Its esiest to belay it from beneath the arete and not from the ledge.

name: Idaho Fall Route
description: This is labelled as it was the probably route of the first ascent. The spire was climbed via a bolt ladder on Mental Hopscotch and then this crack from the ledge to the summit.   Its actually a short little pitch and could be linked with one of the routes below with good rope management. The anchor on the summit is set up to send you down the southwest face.

name: Mental Hopscotch
description: Climb up onto the ledge beneath the north face. Traverse to its far end and find an anchor. Climb the arete clipping the north face bolts.   After estaliching this free climb I found rusted studs in the arete. I believe this was the Idaho Falls Mountaineering Clubs bolt ladder. The climbed the spire via aid, then chopped the ladder on rappel. Their route continued on as "E".

name: Pull the Plug
description: This is a very good limestone sport climb. The route has had only two ascents, so little bits of the surface will be breaking off (as they do on all new-dolomite/limestone climbs in the US, but after a few ascents it will be as clean as can be.   Start the route in an alcove on the southwest face. Move up and right over some loose rock for 15 feet, then onto the proper face. Climb this overhainging wall for 120 feet to the summit, passing a 15 bolts and a rap anchor (part way up) on the way.   Warning: A 70 meter rope only BARELY reaches the ground when rapping from the summit. ITs best to belay on top, lower your partner, and then do the two raps down (From top and halfway station). A 60 meter is no where near the bottom.

name: Walking in L.A.
description: The route climbs roughly the middle of the north face. Its a difficult flash at .12a

name: UNKN
description: crack to bolts to chains

name: "Beer for My Horses"
description: Long slab climb. To start the pitch you can either belay from the first ledge that can be accessed with a easy scramble or you can do the direct start (the direct start was done on the FA) and climb the face of the first ledge. It is about thirty feet to the first bolt when doing the direct start, less if you start from the ledge. There are five bolts and fixed anchors on top. I did have problems with some of the bolts, I used a bolt that I do not normally use at the Hogs Back. All of the bolts are bomb and not cause for real concern, however I did have a problem with bolt number 3, when I went to replace I had the same problem happen. Both of the bolts are fine it is really more of me wanting it to be perfect. For now there are two bolts there, I have plans to replace both. I equalized them together both for the fa. I climbed on a 70m rope and used a tag line to get off. Route song name: "Beer for My Horses (feat. Willie Nelson)"-Toby Keith.

name: "Pretty Pimpin"
description: Climb the corner (gear) into the slab. Climb the slab (bolts) into the roof. From the left hand side of the roof (gear) traverse right under the roof (more gear half way). From the right hand side of the roof climb up to the ledge (bolted anchor).  ”Pretty Pimpin”- Kurt Vile

name: "Touch, Peel and Stand"
description: Climb the thin slab, then climb straight through the roof up to the chains. This route is named after the song "Touch, Peel and Stand" by Days of the New.

name: 99 Problems
description: Short crack, starts behind the pine tree. ”99 Problems”- Hugo

name: I don't want to be
description: The route starts with "Pretty Pimpin" and ends at the chains for "Old Town Road". Two pitches and then some scrambling.  P1: "Pretty Pimpin"-5.8 PG-13 :Climb the corner (gear) into the slab. Climb the slab (bolts) into the roof. From the left hand side of the roof (gear) traverse right under the roof (more gear half way). From the right hand side of the roof climb up to the ledge (bolted anchor). (More beta for "Pretty Pimpin on its page).  P2: 5.5 PG-13. (The gear for P2 is not great and there is not a lot of options). From the chains of "Pretty Pimpin" traverse left into the slot/chimney feature, from there head directly up to the next ledge feature below the staked block feature, next pull the block and gain the next ledge, there are anchors above the block. Finish by scrambling up to the top of the formation to the chains of "Old Town Road".  “I Don’t Want To Be”- Gavin DeGraw

name: Move on
description: Shares the same anchor as “99 Problems”. The route is dirty, but the climbing is fun.   ”Move on” - The Revivalists

name: Old Town Road
description: Face climbing start (bolts) into a finger/hand crack (gear), more face climbing into the top out (bolt) onto the ledge. Easy scramble around the right hand side to access the anchors. “Old Town Road“ - Lil Nas X

name: What's Golden
description: Variation of "Pretty Pimpin". Climb up the slab following the original line of "Pretty Pimpin" up to the roof. Instead of traversing right at the roof continue straight up.  “What‘s Golden”- Jurrasic 5

name: 465 Easy St.
description: Big off width crack in a corner with a funky start. The start is behind a small flake, stem up between the flake and the corner, and mantle up onto a ledge. This is the fork in the road ledge. From here, there are two off widths, this route is the OW on climbers left. Nice mellow grade, becoming more mellow the higher up you go. Great knee jams and arm bar/chicken wings all the way up.

name: 465 Variation
description: This is the more vertical, wide crack the splits off to the right about 3/4 of the way up 465 Easy St.

name: Hearing Voices
description: Starts on splitter finger crack that zig zags up through horizontal cracks to a big ledge. All the cracks give it a blocky, insecure look, but it feels really solid. Right underneath the ledge, rock quality diminishes severely, if you go to far right, it turns into dry mud, just go straight up through the few feet of secure choss and gain the ledge. From the ledge up is a beautiful, slightly overhanging hand crack.     The first section can be bypassed by climbing the beginning of 465 Easy St. up to the Fork in the Road ledge, then traversing over to the crack. Doing this would knock the rating down to 5.9, maybe 5.9+.

name: Live Trap
description: A big, wide, cool looking chimney with an overhang to pull over about halfway up. Unfortunately, the rock condition goes to crap after the pulling through the roof. The tight hand crack on the right side of the upper section feels solid deep in it, sink those cams! But the rest of the rock tends to crumble under you feet. Definitely not for those scared of falling.

name: Mandible
description: Hand crack going up a corner, with a bit of off width at the top. Has a series of gentle grade, then steep grade, gentle grade steep grade. The start requires going up some choss and dried mud for about 10 feet, then solid rock after that. The climbing is pretty straight forward and easy, the protection, not so much. Being creative with the gear is a must.

name: Access Denied
description: Mono crux low and double mono crux high. "At least u rest the rest of your fingers"

name: Amused to Death
description: Just right of the shade tree.  Climbs up the small roof shared with Bravery.  Crux at the lip, then easier but run out climbing above.

name: Beelzebubba
description: Start in a mono and undercling your way up and over a small roof and into a small corner.  Exit the corner on wierd moves, and enter a just-over-vert headwall with mostly good pockets.  This goes on for 5-ish clips.  The bottom is only worth doing for the top.

name: The Brave Cowboy
description: Perhaps the best 5.12a in the Lander area. This route begins on the left side of the main wall at Baldwin. Start up an incipent crack that peters out as the wall steepens. Expect small pockets and crimpers. The crux is around mid height with a "six pack" undercling mono/thumb hold for the left hand. Pumpy and sustained.

name: The Bravery of Being Out of Range
description: Second route right of the shade tree. Bravery goes through the highest part of a small roof.  It has a stinger crux on shallow 2 finger pockets to get over this roof with a ridiculously high left foot.

name: Cowboy This
description: Main wall.  Starts to the right of Supple Cowboy and trends left toward that route.  Very hard bolder problem at 2/3 height.

name: Dinosaur Rock
description: Climb alternating bulge and slab on sustained moves using a variety of pockets.  Good if a 5.10 warm up is needed.

name: Gimmie Shelter
description: Thin climbing leads to an undercling, a couple pulls over a small roof, and a fun, pockety headwall.

name: Grafitti  Man
description: Main wall a few routes right of Brave Cowboy.  Follows a seam up overhanging rock.  Sustained.

name: Little Pedro's Mexican Tidal Wave
description: Start a couple meters left of Brave Cowboy initial corner. Two routes start here; Barbarosa by Frank is the right variation, Little Pedro's Mexican Tidal Wave is the left one. A Steep headwall with big, but flat holds.

name: Losing Streak
description: Climb perfect rock up the blue steak, hard vert-slab climbing.

name: Mask Without a Face
description: Left side of wall.  Shares start with a 13a to its left and climbs up steep rock on good pockets.  Long move/dead point crux.

name: Orange for Anguish
description: Steep climbing on perfect stone.  5.13 to an okay shake and then very hard bouldering up high.

name: Piston Hurricane
description: Right of Bravery.  Good pockets and (you guessed it) a hard sequence over the small roof.

name: Pizza Hut Girl
description: Go up an arete/corner for 2 bolts, then bust right out a wild rail on the lip of the roof. Hard crux as soon as you get your feet under you. go up on cool pockets and continuing steepness.

name: The Power of One
description: Orange streak, center of marquis section of Baldwin Creek Canyon.A classic. Steep, pocketed, pure. Singles at the crux.Juan !$

name: Rain of Gold
description: Far right side of the cliff.  To the left of Orange for Anguish.  Sustained climbing up a steep wall.

name: Supple Cowboy
description: Just right of Cowboy This on the main wall.  This route would be 12c and six stars if not for a ridiculous crimp move in the crux.

name: Tres Amigos
description: Once, the most popular tick in this sector. Tres Amigos has a crux in the low panel, tossing for the white heuco. But more notably the entire top section is on sustained but incut and straight forward, crisp, pumpy but keeper pockets!

name: Troubleshooter
description: Do the first couple moves on the great pockets of Mask Without a Face, then moving up and left into a powerful boulder problem beginning with an undercling, a spock-pocket, then a desperate toss to a good jug and an ok shake.  from here a thin and sequential but slightly easier boulder problem at the top of the bulge guards the slab above.  Great rock and similar to Mask, but with much harder movement.

name: Two Guys Named Festus
description: Next to the lone shade tree (left of it). Starts on underclings. Sequential moves trend right to easier rock above.

name: Viva Hate
description: Savage little number, with complicated movement into gaston dynamics. At least the upper section is straight forward 5.12 pocket climbing.

name: Western Family
description: This verticle seam, Western Family, marks the left margin of the marquis central Sector. Wicked series of micro deadpoints at bolt 4 and finally into decent pockets as the crack dissapears into black colored dolostone.

name: White Lightning
description: The large, white, left facing corner is a good crag organizer.

name: Barber Paradox--Closed
description: Closed as of 11/11/19--added for reference only. Shares start with If By Whiskey.

name: Channel Zero
description: A hard bouldery start leads to thin vertical edge and pocket pulling on beautiful clean rock. A couple big moves on good holds guard the finish up the juggy and gently overhanging  headwall.

name: Dialogical
description: crux between 3-4

name: Feel the Bern
description: Fun, big holds on a southwest facing ramp.  Pulls a small bulge at the top.

name: Fossil Logic
description: Climb the easy but steepening lieback crack, exiting to the right once jugs appear in the steep wave.  pull fun moves through a short bulge.

name: Furniture in Heaven
description: Start up small crimps to begin the slab (crux) and pull onto much better pockets at around the 3rd bolt. The rock quality deteriorates considerably on the second half of the climb. I would not recommend this one, especially compared to other 5.10's like "Two Ducks and an Angel" and "Transitions".

name: Graboids
description: Pull long moves on sharp, distant, but interesting holds until a few jugs at the 4th bolt.  Once the wall steepens, the black streak yields some fun moves on buckets and an exciting runout that is uncharacteristic of usual lander climbing.  Beginning is really just OK, but the top is phenomenal.

name: Happy Feat
description: Good holds up a ramp to a left-facing corner and small bulge.

name: Hell Bent for the Horizon
description: A long line with many challenging pieces to put together. Hard crimping and technical footwork low is the first crux. Make sure your belayer gives you a soft catch, as a hard catch here would smash you into the roof. Above, pocket haul on ever-steepening terrain before a final crux involving long pulls and small holds that require cold and dry conditions. Amazing position on a really cool feature. West facing, gets morning shade. Typical evening Fossil Hill sessions don't work for this guy.

name: If by Whiskey
description: Start 15' left of Kettle Logic. Interesting crux in the middle to steep jugs in upper portion.

name: Ikea in Valhalla
description: Start with thin moves off the ground on two finger pockets to better holds above the second bolt. Cruise up good holds for several bolts to some tricky moves on less than ideal rock right before the anchor. Would be a better climb if the rock was better up high.

name: Kettle Logic
description: Hard boulder moves through second bolt. Small roof then cruising on easier pockets.

name: Liminal Space
description: Thin climbing in lower half can be disorienting. Nice short steep juggy finish.

name: Milk  Bone
description: Sweet, little, orange colored wall, 50m west of Fossil Logic, in nice shady forest. The Wall has a small overhang to start, then decent pockets to a shallow mono crux, right hand single ? Then an easier overhang at the chains. Easy tick for the grade ?

name: No Seat in Hell
description: Climb up to a steeper bulge with interesting slot pockets

name: Tremors
description: Technical wall near the left prow. Protect low V5 boulder problem to side pull, then use pinches and dynamic, matching crimps to pass the crux above bolt 4. And finally into better pockets.

name: Unforgiven
description: Tremors little brother. A flashable .12c espcially if 2nd route warm up is Channel Zero, draws are swapped over while brushing. Consider stick clipping bolt 1. Expect an early crux and another crux at bolt 4.

name: Casual Entertainment
description: Climbs a very blunt arete in the middle of the main wall.  Vertical climbing leads to a steeper bulge at 2/3rds height.  A great jug rest prepares you for the crux bulge just before the anchors using deep small pockets and accurate footwork.

name: Divine Providence
description: Climb the 'Merely Mortal' corner for a few bolts, then bust right on some techy holds. Move up to the base of the roof, and climb through it using a seam and some pockets. Finishes on the headwall. Pretty nice newer line!

name: The Empty Quarter
description: Starts on the thin flake that sounds like a bongo drum left of transitions. After the flake, climb chossy rock with good movement to the roof. Pull the roof, then re-evaluate because the route's not over. Tech your way up the final headwall for 4 or 5 more clips to the anchor.

name: The Full Nickel
description: Begin on a broken, black slabby section which leads to vertical pocket pulls.  Go through a bulge on zig-zagging moves with an interesting crux as the angle eases off.

name: Hang Fire
description: Begin with crimpy moves leading to a big hueco at the third bolt, then through more cruxy bits on varying holds punctuated by the occasional big hold and OK rest oppurtunity every 3rd or 4th move. Then work into a horizontal break before the roof.  Negotiate the bulging roof with big pulls between big holds and enjoy the air below.

name: High Jackers
description: Interesting seam/crack feature that fades then dissapears. Cruxy entry moves leads to High crux, high step, body tension with poor grips.

name: Hips Like Cinderella
description: Face climbing up well spaced bolts to steeper rock at the top.  Intricate with small pockets, crimps, and crappy feet for the first 20 feet or so.  You get to a rest before a bulge, where the business ensues.  Climb out this bulge on pockets, some being a bit less incut than you would like.

name: King of Fools
description: The blunt panel left of “Hips” has a stout and sporty wall. King of Fools revolves  around holding a less than positive heuco above bolt 3 lip and keeping it together on fresh, natural dolomite through a high, easier overhang that guards the anchors.

name: Merely Mortal
description: Begin in a right facing corner, climbing a fingercrack with good locks and good feet.  As the crack ends and the corner gets shallow, clip a bolt, and do a few thin exit moves to the face on the left.  A vertical wall leads through fun moves on holds of increasing size, through a break, and to anchors in a left facing corner.

name: The Motivator
description: Low-angle start to ramp to chimney.  This climb offers stemming or jug-pulling, and is an excellent addition to the crag.

name: Sauce
description: This route was recently re-bolted and re-cleaned after the original FA. The low slab on this line has several thin, footwork intensive moves, and a crux at the first roof that's less than pleasant keeps you honest. Before the chains there is some beautiful rock to finish on. A good route, but it's neighbor, "Hips", deservedly gets more traffic.

name: Show Love
description: Christ on a cracker this thing is full value. It is stiff for the grade, has huge run outs on the upper headwall, crumbly rock, and no lowering chains. Classic.    Start up by utilizing the left arete to gain a jug rail above the first bolt. Traverse right and up on ok holds until you pull onto the upper slab. Now the quest begins up the dirty headwall. There are plenty opportunities to take some massive slab falls on this one so be careful. Thank god it eases up at the last bolt.

name: Space Needle
description: This is a fantastic route.  On par with Hang Fire, but not quite as good.  Start with some fun laybacking past a small tree and get established below the first roof where you can get a great rest.  Pull through the roof on a great flake feature and gain the vertical wall.  Again, another great rest.  Traverse right around the prow and move up on sequential pockets and great feet to another amazing rest (almost no hands) below the final roof.  Pull the final roof on hero jugs and clip the chains!    If I had to identify a crux, I'd say it's pulling the first roof (kind of burly) and then going around the prow and headwall before the second roof (technical and thin).  Think bouldery moves seperated by great rests.

name: Tender Prey
description: Tender Prey is a great route with some unique climbing for the Lander area. Scramble up to the top of the flake to start the climb. The first 4 bolts are the business consisting of side pulls and underclings and some tricky body positioning. After the 4th bolt, the climbing eases up substantially as it follows a nice pocketed face to a roof. The holds above the roof may be difficult to see at first, but they are good.

name: Transitions
description: The first half of this is a fun climb and makes for one of the better 5.10's at Fossil Hill. Start up a large flake that is bolted to the wall and enjoy fun moves up pockets, crimps, and sidepulls to the chains. Continue past the first set of chains to a juggy 5.11c bulge.

name: Two Ducks and an Angel
description: Follow a wandering bolt line up a crack, and then on a thin traverse right to the arete, up the fun arete, and out an airy roof on jugs at the top.  Interesting climbing with many short thoughtful sections separated by relaxed stances.

name: Vision of a Kiss
description: Good, runout face climbing to the roof. While most of the lines to the right have 6 or 7 bolts before the roof, I think this one has 4.... Safe in most places, don't blow the third.  Surmount the bulge on fun jugs and top out on the headwall. A good line that someday, will be rebolted and get climbed more once it's protected with modern spacing.

name: [Redacted]
description: This is an incredible technical rock climb that follows a beautiful orange streak of limestone on the right side of fossil hill. Crimp your way up four bolts with two separate cruxes to a decent stance. Then continue up good holds on the face to one more crux guarding the chains near the last bolt. Brilliant climbing.

name: A Bullet for Mr. Ducky
description: Great climbing up to water groove. Long endurance route on good holds.

name: Big in Japan
description: This is another quality 12- at Fossil Hill. Starts with good vertical climbing on monos and small edges. Larger holds through the bulge and several more bolts leads to the anchor as the angle slabs out.

name: Boom Stick
description: Fun bouldering up a steep wall.  From the left side of the boulder, pull off of a vegetated undercling, maybe a bit of heel hookery, and into cool pockets, working up and right as the going gets alot easier.

name: Enter the Dragon
description: Enter the Dragon climbs up the long less than vertical face on crimps and pockets. The bottom 5 bolts are difficult technical climbing on edges which lead to a nice rest at mid height. Continue up easier climbing on big holds to a final redpoint crux right before the last bolt.

name: Micro Moon
description: Crimps and a few pockets

name: The Righteous and The Wicked
description: Start off on a just past vertical face and pull a small bulge.  The crux is the first few bolts, using crimps and gastons.  Get established on the vertical face above and climb techy rock for 30 or 40 feet, 5.11.  You encounter a steeper finish for the last 2 bolts with a redpoint crux at the end, weighing in at about 12a or b. One of the best 13as in Lander.

name: Snowball for Mr. Bullito
description: Bouldery start then crux relatively low. Varied climbing with great jugs up high.

name: Sun Cup
description: Thin technical climbing with a few pockets mixed in.

name: There Goes My Gun
description: A fun climb, but not quite as good as the 5.11's in the main sector to the left of Hangfire. There are two sets of chains on this one. The first part is a good 5.9 with mostly easy climbing up sidepulls and pockets. You can lower from hooks after the crack ends.  The one bolt extension is the business. Pull the pretty bulge through marginal hard to see pockets. Clipping the bolt is tricky.  *BETA*  Climb left of the first anchor and extension bolt at the top.

name: Valkyrie
description: This route is just right of Righteous and the Wicked. It starts out on a blunt arete and climbs up past crimps and pockets on vertical to gently overhanging rock for the first half.  It is very continuous and technical with no real crux, just an ever increasing pump and fun moves.  If you move to the right down low you can get a great rest on a jug in the middle of this otherwise continuous section.  The conventional wisdom is that this is off route, but this is not a climbing gym so do as you see fit.  The 13a grade assumes that you don't use this rest.  There is a lower angle section next with great rests which are necessary for the upper prow.  This last section is mostly big holds with great movement and 2 crux sections that keep you honest, the last being from the last bolt to the anchor

name: Vortec
description: An ok outing up good but somewhat sharp rock. Step off the flake to thin moves and small monos. Quest up the slab on small nubbins to gain some jugs half way up. Some easy climbing gets you to the base of the bulge, and final crux guards the chains. Gets 10c in the book, but the 3 single pad monos I had to yard on made me think otherwise.

name: Bicameral Mind
description: One of the best in the area! "Bicameral Mind" features some really cool moves on bullet stone, it is well protected and a must do for the area along with "Sweetwater Saloon". Easy start up the flake to some really long moves on decent pockets. This route is pretty continuous featuring some long cross moves on some sinker 2 finger pockets. It's not over until you are over the bulge! Bicameral Mind is from Westworld and is a hypothesis in psychology which argues that the human mind once operated in a state in which cognitive functions were divided between one part of the brain which appears to be "speaking", and a second part which listens and obeys.

name: Dissonance Theory
description: A good warm up for the area. Follow the juggy flake up 3 bolts to a tricky to read crux that involves transferring out onto the face. Make a few long moves, then it is jugs to the top!Dissonance Theory is the state of discomfort felt when two or more modes of thought contradict each other.

name: Hopalong Cassidy
description: Hopalong Cassidy is a nice easier route in the area that climbs the prowl up small dishes and crimps. It gets a little steeper up top to clip the chains, but the holds are good!

name: The Sandworm
description: Bouldery start to some unique climbing on crazy natural holds. Clip the anchors below the overhang.

name: Slinger
description: Climb monos, two finger pockets and edges on a left leaning scoop. Choose between many variation of poor holds and bad feet to a steepening finish.

name: Sweetwater Saloon
description: Start in corner and quickly head left through solid monos and two finger pockets. Consistent and sequencial climbing to a pumpy finish.

name: What The Hale
description: Great moderate! This one consists of mostly big moves on great jugs. The hardest part is lower down on the route, and then eases once you get established with your feet in the big huecos.

name: Day of the Dead
description: This is the King Line of the Dead Zone.  It starts directly below a blunt arete on the left side of the wall.  Start with a difficult boulder problem for a couple of bolts up a clean, sparsely featured face.  Next climb the pumpy arete on decent holds with big reaches. This climb was originally bolted by Todd Skinner in the early 2000s.

name: Dead Man's Party
description: Right side of the Dead Zone.  Start just left of the left hand arête.  The crux is the first couple of moves with a hard right hand side pull mono up to small crimps and eventually to a good pinch.  From here climb up killer stone on steep jugs.  Would be a three star 12b if not for the start.

name: Ex Machina
description: Rightmost route on this section of cliff.  Climb up a large boulder to the right of the arête.  The first clip is a little bit high and a stick clip is encouraged.  Climb the slab for 4 bolts then transition to the steep wall on the right side of the arête.  This route shares anchors with the route to its left.

name: Ghost in the Machine
description: The right arête. Start with the first two bolts stick clipped, as there is no clipping hold for bolt 2 and you could deck if you fall here.  Interesting arête climbing with a perplexing but cool crux between bolts 5 and 7.  This route is as good as any in the Lander area and on bullet proof rock.

name: The Walking Dead
description: Left side of the Dead Zone. This route starts on a crack and then traverses at bolt four to climb a blunt arête. It is a link up. The crux is between bolts six and eight with sequential movement on crimps and pockets. The straight up line, called Day of the Dead, adds a v9 crux start that raises the grade to 14a.

name: Walking With a Ghost
description: Left most route on this wall.  It follows a crack for its entirety.  Sustained and pretty cool.

name: Burn, Baby, Burn
description: Start in a corner for the first two bolts. The first few moves are shared with Holy Smoke, but the bolts are not.  The crux is pulling past bolt 2 through a little bulge and getting established on the face above. From here it's probably 5.11 with fun moves on good pockets. Good second pitch.

name: Fire in the Hole
description: Leftmost route on the wall, left of the arête. Climb vertical rock up slopey crimps and pockets for 8 bolts. It's probably about 12b to the roof.   Next pull the small roof on jugs to gain a vertical headwall above. The crux is the last two bolts. Expect cryptic footwork to move between small positive pockets and crimps

name: Holy Smoke
description: Follows a crack on the right side of the wall.  It shares the first few moves with the route to its right (Burn, Baby, Burn), but it has its own protection bolts.  The first 4 of these are sustained steep pulling on sidepulls with a neat heel hook sequence.  This is probably around 12b.  You next follow the crack up to a small roof with good holds and numerous rests.  This is easy 5.11 climbing for 6 or 7 bolts.  There is a great rest at the roof.  Next comes the crux, pulling the small bulge and moving left to a slot.  Climbers with short arms may find the crux sequence very difficult as there are really no intermediate holds.  Finish up the beautiful headwall passing one more bolt to a two bolt anchor.

name: Liar, Liar, Pants on Fire
description: Clean face climbing, starting from the right and traversing slightly left after bolt two. The bottom is quite tricky and there is a bouldery move between bolt 4 and 5. This was supposed to be the 5.10 warm up but it did not turn out that way.

name: Rising from the Ashes
description: Sustained pocket pulling up a gently overhanging wall for 8 bolts.  The hardest moves are between bolts 3 and 4, but there is no real rest until the second to last bolt.  One more crux after this shake guards the anchors.  I fell off clipping the chains before I finally redpointed this one.

name: Spontaneous Combustion
description: The left arête on the wall. Scramble up on a small ledge to gain the first bolt. Clip number two from a left hand side pull, then start hugging up the arête. There is a crux between bolts four and five, followed by a decent rest. Next surge up some more difficult climbing to the hardest part of the route between bolts six and seven.  From the right hand clip hold at bolt 6, you bump twice with the left to a good sidepull pocket, cross over to a tight right hand 2 finger, and then up to a hueco just past bolt 7.  Milk an okay rest here and fire past one more crux at bolt eight. Tenuous feet, a small right hand crimp, an inobvious left hand side pull, and a wide left hand pinch on the arête leads up to the anchor.  You might want to skip the last bolt because there is no real clipping hold.  It's a pretty long fall, but safe.

name: Zozobra
