From the saddle traverse right on easy ledges until below the south face of the summit block.  Some gully like cracks lead to any easy finish.    Rappel bolt are on the NE corner.  A second set of "mid way" rap bolts is at the flake on the NE side of the pinnacle.

name: Inaugural Address
description: From a ledge on the east face of the ridge begin the crack at the left set of bolts.  The crux is the getting thru the pinched out seam and back on to easier crack with one bolt along here for pro.  The crack above is an easy cruise.

name: Late Sleeper--Late Show
description: A steep parallel hand crack angle right and then strainght to a ledge with bolts anchors.

name: Overhang Bang
description: From the saddle of traverse right to the summit boulder of Friend Pinnacle and climb the bulging-overhanging finger crack & face.

name: Saddle Battle
description: Intermittant crack and face to an alcove and some figuring to set up for the last bulge.

name: Skinny Jenny
description: A classic short route in a corner with only a few good holds

name: The Tackle for Trout
description: Mostly face and crack on prow/arete of the end of the ridge.

name: Traverse Master
description: Climb the crack in the corner to near the saddle and then traverse left on the steep face & crack to the left side of the face of the pinnacle.  Anchor bolts here.

name: Trout Line
description: Climb the steep gully formed where the ridge going north broadens.  The crux in the gully section is getting stood up on the projecting rock piece where the angle steepens.  Soon move left onto the ridge face for pitch 2 and work your way to ridge.  Once on the ridge I preferred staying roped up going to the rap bolts towards the south end of this ridge .  A spectacular view and feeling along this narrow strangely shattered pressure ridge, but good solid rock.

name: Barmore's Brothel
description: Barmore's Brothel is about how you spend your stored energy while on the steep hard line Woody chose. There are a couple of ways to go around a difficult zone using the same bolt as the highest protection below.

name: Cross Fit Bottle Training
description: Cross Fit Bottle Training is a steep/mild overhanging face on the black amphibolite wall at the base of the Krumblings Towers Center. The rock is solid and mostly big holds but with difficult exits from positions.

name: Liberal Dogma
description: Liberal Dogma leaves the Central Hub anchors and makes an exit to the left.  This route offers the easiest way off the towers other than rappelling.  The moves left and up from the anchors are hardest on both pitches and  well placed bolt protects these moves.

name: The Republican Way
description: The Republican Way obviously is an exit to the right to get off the Center Wall by going into a side gully with little change in elevation but some slippery slopes and obstacles make the exit less pleasing than it looked from the start.  The traverse could be done either way but the fixed protection is better placed for an exit from the center rightward.  The route is better done as 2 pitches or climb in tandem to reduce rope drag.

name: Spike Jones and the City Slickers
description: Spike Jones and the City Slickers follow the angling line of corner up an left from the Central Hub.  The first two steep sections are part of Liberal Dogma but the Spike Jones route follows the corner right on up through the steep overhanging diherderals to a flat summit top of the left tower and next to the marble tower.

name: Laird's Layer Cake
description: When the river is down a climbing team can belay from a pile of rocks at the base of this climb that is in the large pool of still water in the river channel.  The climb is steep with interesting face.

name: Art & Science
description: Follow a slanting crack system to a ledge and exit left.

name: Cougar Chase
description: A crack with short runs of various sizes.

name: Flat Rabbit
description: a tight seam and thin crack on a moderate angle dome.

name: A Victory 4 Same Sex
description: A Victory 4 Same Sex is a gentle fem line that won't scar your hands but some crack tech will help.

name: I will Strap it ON
description: Strapping it on is what you get when you are willing to take a ride on scant face but the route is equpped for safety.

name: My Favorite Enema
description: My Favorite Enema will require some crack perversion  for your hands to hold the rock.

name: My Wife Stretches with Cathy
description: This line of bolts may be a hard climb for short people but it was done by a short hard man.

name: No Anal Re-tension Here
description: Do hold back on using some gear for this big one.

name: Shoulder Scolder
description: Shoulder Scolder is great route with many perplexing moves and some are slippery.

name: Sunday Morning Sunshine
description: A crack and face sport climb with bolts that has good sun in the morning.

name: T'was on My Face
description: T'was on My Face starts near My Favorite Enema but most of the face moves are on the minor prow at the end of the climb while most of the lower route is crack and stemming.

name: Unscanned Territory
description: Very Long reaches lead to an almost featureless face.

name: Douhitt Booty
description: Double Cracks to intermittent crack through bulges.  The First bulge is the crux and could go on gear, but the 2 bolts preserve the best holds.  Enjoy.

name: Grin and Barrett
description: Great slab climb on fun holds, crux is the top with interesting holds and slippery feet.

name: Keel Haul
description: Climb the Beautiful patina corner past one bolt then trend right to top.  Crux at the top of the corner.

name: Queen Anne's Revenge
description: Mixed Route follow middle crack on right side of the pirates cove past 2 bolts through or over a wide flaring crack to join keel haul through to the shared anchor.

name: Blunt Aawareness
description: Start in a crack system right of the large LF dihedral. Follow flakes and face climbing to the anchors.  Still a little dirty but worth doing if in the area.

name: Christie's Babies Look Like Zach
description: Some crack moves will get U up to the slab face.

name: Defying My GayDar Signals
description: A bolted face climb with stemming start and some small grit crimpers.

name: Douhitt Flow
description: Follow a left facing dihedral on great rock with nice patina face holds to a roof.  Traverse right under the roof and finish up and left to the anchors.  A high quality outing...

name: Mark's Pepper Seed N-fection
description: A short face climb on the shady side of the gully.

name: Masquerading as a Teenage Lesbian
description: A mildly burly move will get you unto the face from the crack start.

name: My Last Crack
description: Follow this black lichen covered smooth crack.

name: Orange Marmalade
description: This route is on the cover of the new guide book for the Laramie Range.  It might be the best route in the Stuffed Canyon area!  Following interesting patina face climbing to a steep bulge.  Think fast the clock is ticking.    Do this route!

name: Poverty Trap
description: This great warmup follows a featured slab 25ft to the right of a large LF dihedral.  There are a lower set of anchors for top roping and a higher set for rapping.

name: Unknown Lieback
description: Climb start of Poverty Trap and head up the obvious bolted lieback crack to open shuts.

name: Sure-Go-Mag-no-Leo
description: Sure-Go-Mag-No-Leo is the prominent line on westmost corner of the Cone.  Staying with the usable face takes a lot of movement left and right and there are some bulges to deal with finding the hidden hand hold.  We did the climb as 2 80' pitches at 11b and about 50' to the summit at 5.6.

name: Tweeter and the Fireflies
description: Getting started on Tweeter and the Fireflies is the hardest move on this slab route.

name: School House Monkey
description: Follow the various crack systems beginning on most eastern buttress of the east face

name: Instant Access
description: This route is the easy access way to the top of a bulge and the difficult move are near the top.

name: Joy Tour the World
description: A short route next to the trail with some steep face to manage on typical Reese Mt Granite.

name: Lickity Splat, Zachity Zach
description: A short route up a moderate line of odd mix of hand holds.

name: Merely Mesmerized
description: The trailside route follow a line on the big holds just left of Instant Access.

name: Monopoly
description: This south facing route is thought to be the elegant steep and straight handcrack that begins on dark brown buttress about 60 feet above Duck Creek Streambed.

name: Shirtless in Siberia
description: This is listed as route #14, “Moscow Circus Project” in the Orenczak guidebook. My thanks goes out to him for putting in the bolted anchor up top. Start with a hand crack in the center of the wall, transition left at a shelf to the cupped hands/fist crack and follow continuous jamming through several breaks to the top of the formation.

name: Eviction
description: The leftmost established route begins in an open book near the center of the crag itself. Head up the slabby open book as it pushes you up left. Execute a wonderfully balancy crux at two-thirds height and find an anchor on the ledge. The first two bolts are missing hangers.

name: Livable Level of Decency
description: This is listed as route #17, “Roof Crack Project” in the Orenczak guidebook. The first two bolts are missing hangers but most stickclips should be able to reach the third. Juggy holds lead to a juggy layback crack, followed by a juggy lip encounter via huge holds and hand jams. The climbing is quite excellent and highly recommended.

name: Smokin' Bob's Crack
description: An eyecatching splitter crack with a change in size at the roof and near vertical.  The rock type is a metamorphic granite gneiss.

name: What the Big Boys Eat
description: What the Big Boys Eat is a spectacular splitter roof that has a zone of 4.25 inch fists which is Bob's unique size.  For others the move will be offwidth.  The climb even for hand of Bobs size  was quite a puzzle for him to figure out taking him several days of flights to redpoint.

name: Cytokine Storm
description: The hardest parts of this climb are just above the  bottom and near the top.  Local route finding along the way, as to whether to go left or right above a bolt figures into the less than obvious best pathway choices.  usually these are from a ledge.

name: Enchi Minni Off-Width
description: This is an off-width start to "Enchi, Minnie, Oye".  Off width crack until you get to the area you traverse to flared crack to finish.

name: Enchi minni oye
description: Main climb on this wall.  This is the small hand/finger crack just right of the arete.  Starts out with foot jam in crack and plenty of hands, including under cling in horizontal crack.  Moves up on a ledge where you have to traverse over to flared crack with plenty of face holds that you follow to top.

name: Matt's Tiny Crack
description: Face climb with lots of jugs that is easily protected with 2-3 cams in hand-sized crack.

name: Twitter Fingers
description: Nice little finger crack with lots of feet that help the marginal finger placements.

name: Alien Dave's Last Meal
description: This long pitch cover mostly easy face with only one well bolted 5.10 face zone.  This may have been Alien Cam Maker Dave Waggoner's last Climb.  He died of liver failure but he did like beer and ....

name: Back Side Pleasure
description: Some holds and features here and there will get you up this mild overhanging in the shade face.

name: Roofing Crew
description: A roof crack leads to easier face.

name: Saving Face
description: This roof like face climb makes use of the horizontal holds formed by the projecting plates of granite.

name: A Blast from the Past
description: A low angle start that steeps near the finish.

name: A Lube Job on Tiger Rock
description: Climb some steep bulges on big hold and some slippery slab.

name: A Roof for all Seasons
description: This roof route passes through a low roof, up some easy slab on onto some some steep horizontal and finihes with a friction traverse.

name: Aid Line for Free
description: A well bolted short face.

name: Broken Rib Training
description: Mostly a slab climb on an arete face with small holds, some high steps and good pro.

name: Corn Dog
description: Called "Corn Dog" and rated 5.10 in the error-filled Laramie Range Guide (LRG), this is a challenging warm-up...    Moderate crack and face climbing protected by gear leads to the right edge of a large roof.  A heady move takes you to the top of a pillar where you clip the first bolt. Pull the roof via a short strenuous 10+/11- section.  Head up the arete and face to the base of the roof.      (NB Difficult 3rd clip unless you go past it to goods holds and clip it down and to your left.)  2 bolts out left force the climb through the steepest part of the roof to a desperate top out.  Or, to keep the climb in the mid 11 range, from the horizontal at the base of the roof climb out right for an easier exit.  Adding a bolt would create a better exit and protect good climbing straight up the face at the right edge of the roof about 10' right of the current bolted finish. No anchors.

name: E-Cig Dreams
description: A steep face climb with some hand hold emimination leads to easier going.

name: Event Horizon
description: Link together a system of cracks to get up and right  on this central portion of the Meadows Mound.

name: Half Pipe Dreams
description: Several overhang alcoves give a standing tuck to find the best combination for exit out of a leaning out position.

name: Learning Sex from Sandusky
description: a stiff line with some neat positions

name: Out Reach Upmanship
description: A low angle ramp of rock lead to a smooth looking vertical face of of rock with mostly horizontal cracks for hanging on.

name: Para Fin
description: A steep arete climb leads to some steep face to the anchors.

name: Rat's Nest
description: Some steep, awkward crack at the start closes and the line continues through the overhanging holds and onto a sparsely bolted slab going rightward.

name: Revert to a Pervert
description: Revert starts at a low angle but soon reverts to an angle that perverts have fun on but with big holds.

name: Right of Revert to Pervert
description: Follow bolts up nice golden granite prow just right of the black scooped face of Pervert. Engaging moves up side-pulls and underclings with thin crux at top. Best of the bolted moderates here.

name: Schwartzchild Radius
description: Follow this right facing dihederal to its end and proceed with the roof above.

name: Tiger Woods Me on Tiger Rock
description: Trample up this tiger skin looking rock over some easy slab and some bulges.

name: Tribute to Tara and Todds Liver
description: Obvious crack through roof located between Out Reach Upmanship (named Duck's Breath in Laramie Range Guide) and Para Fin (named Postcards From the Edge in Laramie Range Guide). Start next to new bolted route The Pirate and the Chain Gang (FA Orenczak and Lynn May 31 2015).  Use these anchors for descent or top out following corner crack system.  Use new Laramie Range Guide Book for details on Duck's Breath and Postcards from the Edge.  FA of Tribute to Tara and Todds Liver on May 31, 2015 by Ryan Miller and Deke Doty.  Named in honor of the live liver donation of Tara Miller to Todd Pepper which saved his life.

name: Short & Stocky
description: a hand crack with a wide pod

name: World Traveler
description: Stem and face climb up the left facing corner.

name: All My Men Wear Bras
description: A south facing face climb with a couple of bulges.

name: Push Again
description: Some hard stemming and crack work will get you through this deceptive and short problem.

name: Rancho Delito
description: A steep gray face with a few holds leads left to a dished out area and next some yellow slab.

name: Hollywood Propaganda
description: Vertiacal start with a prominent diagonal dyke to easy slab. overhanging bulge with good crimps to rap anchors

name: Matt's Crack
description: Tricky vertical start to easy slab. hand crack roof to rap anchors

name: Red Zephyr
description: 7th bolted route from the left on the wall. 2nd pitch is 5.4. Slabby

name: Stellar Ascension
description: Slabby feet, jug hands. Up corner, bolts are hidden in the shade at the top of the corner.

name: Bonnie Lass
description: Bonnie Lass is a moderately steep face climb on the black colored north facing wall of Gneiss Canyon.

name: Compelling Pinches
description: A face climb that angle to the right into a more desparate single pinch face move to a more difficult clip.

name: Cryatal Power
description: Some large brown crystals permit movement thru  a zone of steep rock.

name: Daylight Hibernator
description: Mostly face with a few intermittent cracks.

name: Diamond in the Lichen
description: You must like razor-crimping to appreciate this edging test piece. Find an orange lichen streak 20 feet left of Fish Angling. Stick clip the first bolt and then angle up left along the incipient seam to an intimidating mantel. Once on the ledge, regain your composure before flowing up terrifically fun edges that leads to a brief crack section. Swing left and up to the anchor in a hanging left-facing dihedral.

name: Eye Bleech
description: Start under a four-foot roof that begins about 12 feet off the ground. Power out the roof and continue up a sustained face, catching rests where you can as this thing never lets up until the chains are clipped.

name: Fish Angling
description: Fish Angling slants up & to the right using face and crack.

name: Genuine Ostrich (3 Payments)
description: Begin about 40 feet right of Fish Angling and 10 left of Eye Bleech. Swing up jugs to a prominent fin jutting out of the wall at the third bolt. Sink the locker kneebar, fire the crux, and enjoy mellow, 5.10 climbing to the anchor.

name: Gneiss Task
description: A continual steep climb on the blocks of rock that goes past some bulges that are separated with intermittent cracks.

name: Lean Off
description: Lean Off follows a steep wide shallow crack slot that right leans upward and cross a few block tops to the anchors.

name: Managing Tight Lips
description: Managing Tight Lips is on the yellow-brown south facing wall and has only a shallow lip after the thin crack pinches out.

name: Movie Making
description: An easy line leads to the final zone of moves that are so obvious.  Crack & face

name: New Route Goofin'
description: Head 100 yards left from Fish Angling to find this sport route on a tan buttress. Pull over a small overlap and then swim up jugs to the sixth bolt. Make a sneaky transition hard right and then up to the last bolt. Cut right again into a hidden hand crack/corner (optional #2 Camalot) and climb to a ledge with a bolted anchor. The rock is a bit crumbly and the sequences can be hard to read. With that said, I thought it was still a fun warm up for the area.

name: Sleep Master
description: Face up a steep slab with some crack moves.

name: Staged Access
description: Staged Access has some face traverse moves left to gain access to a set of chimneys and blocks leading to the grand stage above.

name: Zapateria la Bailarina
description: The upper crack really draws the eye and I was so happy a series of holds lead directly up to it. This is the rightmost route on the panel currently. Begin about 10 feet right of Eye Bleech, under a series of small roofs. Work your way through the overlaps to then angle up right to the hanging crack system. Be pleasantly surprised to find a hand crack in what appears to be a fist or offwidth crack and jam the left-angling crack to a ledge with a bolted anchor.

name: Zarathruster
description: An steep arete line with the usual holds here and there.

name: Alice in Wonderland
description: This amazing and exposed line starts at the very center of the Neverland Wall formation. After a super engaging 5.7 first pitch, gain the Headwall for a fun long easy 5.11 with a 12a crux thrown into the beginning. The views are spectacular.

name: Tad's Route (name pending)
description: Amazing two pitch sport climb - p1 is a long 5.7 approach pitch to a great stance and then embark on one of the coolest looking aretes anywhere.

name: The Aussie Chickenwalk
description: Starts on the left side of the Book Pages Wall and climbs straight up PAST the bolts.

name: Flight Behavior
description: Climbs just left of the V-notch water streak.  Begins directly above the small tree.

name: Gravity's Rainbow
description: Climbs past the right facing truncated pages and past the alcove.

name: The Great Pancake Escape
description: Climbs up the middle of the wall.  Don't forget the syrup ...

name: The Monkey Wrench Gang
description: The Monkey Wrench Gang is located just right of the V-notch water streak.  Start from the small tree or further right along the traverse.  Pad up the slabs and pass the truncated page that forms a small right facing corner. Jam, pinch, undercling, and palm your way to the top.

name: The Old Man and the Sea
description: Climbs up the V-notch water streak.

name: *"Anne's Route"
description: Second pitch.

name: *Boulder Fields
description: Second pitch.

name: *Cornerstone Crack
description: Climbs the crack on the left side of the large Cornerstone Block at the skyline.

name: *Decaying
description: Moves up and left from the top of Kaying to fire up a weakness in the short, steep, dark brown wall above.

name: *Eat a Lotta Peaches
description: Climbs the shallow crack system that splits the dark brown varnished rock on the steep right side of the Cornerstone Block.

name: *Isolation
description: Second pitch above Poverty of Ambition

name: *Phineas Gage
description: Climb steep crack on the headwall above Just Another Saturday Night. The climbing is more fun than an accidental frontal lobotomy.

name: *Project "Power Roof"
description: Horning.

name: *Project "Short Steep Crack"
description: Laird

name: *Sport Trindleberg
description: Sage advice from the Reverend Sport Trindleberg, "Fear, like pain, may just be Gods way of hurting us."    Climbs straight up from the top of Kaying or Ben's Barbeque and then trends right along a shallow seam to pass over the steep overlap.

name: *Sunday Morning Coming Down
description: Climbs the steep headwall above and to the right of Just Another Saturday Night. If you need beta, ask the man in black over a breakfast beer.

name: Abstract Realty
description: Start on steep rock, move into the short shallow dihedral, work right to the arete and continue up.

name: Badger Tracks
description: Badger Tracks is three pitches that trend up and right to reach the summit ramp. Can be used to access the start of Eat a Lotta Peaches, which ascends the right side of the large Cornerstone Block at the skyline.    P1:10b, Slab up and right to short open book headwall. Grab on and pull down ... (All bolts to open shuts, 70')    P2:10a, Ascend the hand crack corner and then step/traverse right (All bolts to cold shuts, 40')    P3:10, Climb the face (probably all bolts ... to cold shuts, 95')

name: Beautiful Loser
description: Where you gonna fall ... when you realize ... you just can't have it all.  Climbs a series of sidepull/layback flakes up questionable rock.  Belay off to the side.

name: Ben's Barbecue
description: Starts on steep rock in the gully just to the right of the small cone. Pass the two horizontal seams and continue straight up to anchor.

name: Beta Licker
description: Slab up to the overhang then power and finesse into the open dihedral. Work your way past the second overhang to reach the anchor. The popular option of linking the Beta Licker to the end of the Down Converter has been dubbed Beta Converter, 12a, which provides three distinct cruxes.

name: Brushed Off
description: Just right of Sex at Noon Taxes, angle right across the slabby panel and continue up.

name: Calypso
description: Start on steep, unobvious rock to move up to the right side of the slabby ramp; fun, airy traverse left to reach the arete.

name: Cloudy With A Chance Of Lichening
description: To keep this at 5.7, the direct start climbs the steeper slab just left of pine tree to the high first bolt just under the small (1') roof. Step through the small roof and continue up the center of the licheny slab and continue into the right-facing dihedral with a couple bushes.    Route can be climbed at 5.6 by taking ramp to left and stepping right around the small roof after clipping the first 2 bolts.    Named for the rumbling thunder while bolting the route and slippery lichen on the FA.

name: Cocoa Free Blue
description: Climbs the short slab and fires out the short headwall splitter crack feature.

name: Dinging of Dented McGee
description: Follows the crack system through the roof located 20 feet above the ground. Continue up the crack system.

name: Down Converter
description: Follow the steepening cracks to reach the top of the flake ledge. Pass the Beta Licker anchor at 80 feet to continue up and delicately move left to gain the larger holds on the skyline. Climbing only the first 80 feet to Beta Licker anchor is 5.10+.

name: Fire on the Mountain
description: Pass to the right of the overhang on the slabby tongue of rock and continue up the arete.

name: Gonad Crunch
description: Step onto the wall, pass two horizontal seams, and follow the left edge of the steep varnished wall. Finishes on Red Mite anchor or can trend right to Kaying anchor.

name: Greased Lichening
description: Easy climbing up a ramp and past a coffee table sized boulder to the high first bolt.  Traverse left into the right-facing dihedral.  Crux is in the first 3 bolts after which stemming in the dihedral is your friend.

name: Just Another Saturday Night
description: Climb up 20 feet and move right into the dihedral. Enjoy the stemming to the top.

name: Kaying
description: Step right onto wall, pass two horizontal seams, pull onto the headwall, and move through the small alcove below the small triangular overhang.

name: Kibosh
description: Enjoy the jugs on the overhanging start and get those feet established above the roof.  Follow easier rock up.

name: Leading Edge
description: Step onto wall, pass two horizontal seams, pull into the scoop, and follow the right edge of the steep varnished wall.

name: Luteus Maximus
description: Climbs the left side of the small cone that sits at the base of the wall.

name: Mitey Red
description: Pull the steep start and move up the thin, overlapping bulges above.

name: Never to Grow Old
description: Overhanging start to a second short steep section.  Follow easier rock up.

name: Poverty of Ambition
description: Steep, thin crack.

name: Putain is not French for Piton
description: A few steep jugs lead to easier climbing before committing to the final crux moves.  Can be climbed using 5.11 or 5.10 moves.

name: Red Mite
description: Make the airy step left onto the wall and follow the large edges upwards. At top the direct finish above the last bolt is 5.10a/b, traversing right towards the small pine is 5.9

name: Royal Flush
description: Ascends the steep water groove through two overhangs.

name: Sex at Noon Taxes
description: Great movement up the blocky, changing corners and past the horizontal seams onto the ramp above.  Use the midway anchor or bring a few pieces of small gear to finish the short crack to the top anchor.

name: Slice of Time
description: Starts at the slab of Cocao Free Blues and angles left to romp up even more slabby climbing.

name: Thieving Dingus Didn't Get This
description: After the steep start follow the climbing of the water streak to the anchor.

name: Traverse Pitch
description: Traverses up and right to the start of Royal Flush

name: *Alien Fabric
description: Alien Fabric is located on the short, overhanging headwall above the middle of Douglas Park.

name: Aeoleus
description: Aeoleus follows the left-trending crack and dihedral system that passes on the left side of the largest midcliff, 20-foot wide overhange. Spectacular stemming and arete positioning. Aeoleus anchors provide the best rappel (100' free) into Douglas Park.

name: Early Timing
description: At the fourth bolt, the route moves left.

name: Hanging of Yellowstone Kelley
description: Hanging of Yellowstone Kelley follows the minor weakness that passes on the left side of two overhangs at 25 feet and 50 feet.

name: Mind is a Minefield
description: Climb past the twiggy tree at the start, step left, and follow the bolts ... up.

name: Open Project "Oblique Overlap"
description: Some cleaning, not bolted. Laird.

name: Sonic Hedgehog
description: Sonic Hedgehog follows the minor weakness that passes on the right side of the largest midcliff, 20-foot wide overhang. The climbing is continuous to the end.

name: Witness
description: Climbs through the left side of the black lichen overhang at 25 feet. Follows the weakness to the top.

name: Hot Corner
description: Climb slab to left-facing corner at the top.

name: McGee Slab
description: Steep start to slab.

name: Cake Walk
description: Starts from right side of Amphitheater and trends right.  Use long draws to lessen rope drag.

name: Fading in My Own Parade
description: P1-12b, 100', 17QDs: Climbs the weakness 5 feet to the right of the large overhanging ear through the middle of the Amphitheater overhangs.   P2-8, 60': Continues to top.

name: Pseudo Scalars
description: On left side of Amphitheater.

name: The Roof Launch
description: P1-11d, 100', QDs and small to med cams: Meander up the slabs for 40 feet, climb the splitter crack in the left facing dihedral to move under the large roof. Launch through the notch out the middle of the roof.   P2-10+, 80', QDs: Continue to summit.

name: Twenty Red Lights
description: And the preacher said, 'You know, you always have the Lord by your side'. And I was so pleased to be informed of this, that I ran 20 red lights in His honor. Thank you Jesus, thank you Lord.    P1-11c, 100', 12QDs: Twenty Red Lights passes under the small triangular roof and trends left following featured rock.   P2-8, 60': Continues to summit.

name: "Unnamed Lucky Amnesia Route"
description: Bolted.

name: *Both Sides Now
description: Climb underside of ramp to vertical crack. About 20 feet up crack move left on edge of flake and up face holds to the end of the dihedral and then back left to coldshuts.

name: *Boy Toy
description: Use Rope Tricks or the via ferrata to access the second major ramp.   Pitch 1, 10c, ascends the face above the ramp to reach a slopey belay ledge and the base of the overhanging Driess Wall.   Pitch 2, 11d, shoots out the middle of the steep Driess Wall.

name: *Fool's Gold
description: Follow the lower portion of the Upper Ramp to reach the Upper Vertical Face. Fool's Gold steps onto the left side of the Upper Vertical Face using a brown bolt hanger and continue climbing using mostly big holds and sometimes the arete.

name: *Free Loading Freddie
description: Climb 10 feet, traverse right 12 feet, climb while angling left of the overhanging kidney stone to short slab beneath undercut face. From edge of steeply dumping ramp angle right to next undercut block. Surmount overhang and angle left to summit coldshuts.

name: *Freeze Fry
description: Step up onto the Upper Ramp and follow it to just below the short vertical corner between the steepening Upper Ramp and the Upper Vertical Face on the left. Freeze Fry steps onto the right side of the Upper Vertical Face using a chain-link hanger (may be replaced). Continue climbing occasionally pulling on the protruding ends of flakes.

name: *Gamma Bursts
description: Climb the major overhanging left leaning dihedral to the three-faced corner of the highest roof. rappel ropes from the three-faced corner lands at the top of Nazi Regalia. Or a short pitch to the right will get you out from under the roof (5.11b/c).

name: *Getting 86ed
description: P1-10d,90': 6 QDs, sm-med cams. From coldshuts in semi-bow area climb left on ramp to crack and continue up. Above roof traverse right to crack and continue through orange fact to belay coldshuts.   P2-12a,90': 2 QDs, black and blue aliens and sm-med cams. Climb left and gain ledge above belay bolts. Traverse left to crack and continue up and around roof and up a face with a bolt. Traverse right on dumping ramp to a bolt and climb the final overhang to coldshuts.

name: *Open Project
description: Bolted route ascends the steep right side of the Driess Wall.

name: *Oscar Pickerel
description: Ascends the obvious splitter finger crack in the middle of the cliff.    Start by stepping right past the roof, up the thin seam, through the notch, and up the SW-facing splitter crack. Finish the route by following the slab (gear) to a few steep moves to reach the apex of the second major ramp or continue straight up from the splitter crack past two bolts (10+) to the anchor at the top of Both Sides Now.

name: *Overland
description: Trends up and right.

name: *Parallel Transport
description: Follows the seams above Positive Illusions and moves right at the top to reach the Nazi Regalia belay ledge.

name: *Plumbago
description: This overhanging pitch goes up and left from the Nazi Regalia ledge.  Near the final overhang (the skyline from the belay) are two equal level bots about 3 feet apart. Going left is easier. Consider unclipping the third bolt to reduce rope drag. Do not expect to successfully rappel and pull ropes with anything less than two ropes each at least 120-foot long.

name: *Reeses Pieces
description: Reeses Pieces trends up and right.

name: *Ride Steppenwolf
description: Using the same start as Fool's Gold, follow the lower portion of the Upper Ramp to reach the Upper Vertical Face. Ride Steppenwolf moves onto the middle of the Upper Vertical Face using a gray cold shut. The route utilizes sidepulls, edges, and pinches.

name: *Scarpelli's Belly
description: Splitter crack through the down-turned overhanging roof above the left side of the Nazi Regalia ledge.

name: [Redacted]
description: Nazi Regalia follows the vertical, blocky cracks that are directly below the large, upper roofs of the Hightower, which resemble an inverted staircase.   The upper section of the route has 10-foot wide blank faces to both sides of the route. The route provides quick access to the wide Nazi Regalia ledge and the routes above. There are several starts of varying difficulty ranging from 5.9 on the left to steep 5.10 on the right.

name: Block Party
description: Block Party follows the blocky features just to the right of the 10-foot wide blank face to reach the Nazi Regalia Ledge.

name: Casting Line
description: Casting Line climbs the right side of the broken band of rock that Block Party using a totally separate path to reach the Nazi Regalia Ledge.

name: Crossover
description: Start on the slab below the overhanging incline face, moving left under the protruding fins of the perched tower and finishing on Casting Line to reach the Nazi Regalia Ledge.

name: Cyritos the Kat
description: Short face climb with interesting moves.

name: Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test
description: Climb 20 feet of crack to reach a sloping ledge. Climb the left side of the arete until you reach the jugs and delicately crossover to the right side of the arete.

name: Leftover Love and Still Horny
description: Climbs a short slab, transitions through some steeper small overlaps and corners to reach the "pinchout" of the first major ramp.

name: Mill Iron Spear
description: Begin right of Casting Line using an angle iron bolt hanger prior to reaching the ledge at base of the shallow dihedral with a short 1-inch wide section of crack. Continue climbing toward the left side of a perched tower of protruding fins at 60 feet. Traverse right above its roof and continue up 40 feet and then trough another roof and up to the far right side of the Nazi Regalia Ledge.  You are now sitting on Hemorrhoid Point

name: Positive Illusions
description: Positive Illusions occupies the slab left of Nazi Regalia. The feet-trusting move takes one left into a short dihedral and ends at the stat of Parallel Transport.

name: Ramp Pitch
description: Access pitch to traverse the first major ramp across the "pinchout" and lead to the "semi-bowl flat area".  Provides easy access to the starts of Oscar Pickerel, Getting 86ed, Parallel Transport, and Both Sides Now.

name: Rope Tricks
description: Rope Tricks follows the rusty-colored, blocky, vertical bedding between the first major ramp and the second major ramp. The great climbing is very continuous.

name: What You Don't Have
description: Climb the easy, blocky start to reach the minor ramp. Move up the steep face/seam, angle right and follow the wide crack to the top.

name: Wuss Route
description: Easy

name: Candy Store Cowboy
description: Follows the slabs and cracks ten feet left of the mostly brown blank face.

name: Gap Route
description: Climbs the slabby crack and dihedral system 30 feet to the left of the large left-facing dihedral.

name: Project "Crackuss"
description: Laird

name: Project "Faceuss"
description: Laird

name: Takin' Care of Business
description: Located on right side of John Prine Wall.

name: Taxi Dancehall
description: Climbs the face 10 feet to the left of the large left-facing dihedral.

name: Baby Bear
description: Climbs the shallow stemming dihedral.

name: Goldilocks
description: Work up the slab and then step off ledge onto vertical face above.

name: Momma Bear
description: Ascend the less than vertical, pocketed, water streak on large holds.

name: Poppa Bear
description: Climbs the short steep face.

name: *"Unnamed Various Thin Cracks"
description: A couple discontinuous systems of thin cracks extend above the right side of the Rendezvous Buttress Slab.

name: *Chirality (Right and Left)
description: These two splitter cracks lie above and left of the Rendezvous Buttress summit, where the slabby apron of the buttress meets the main headwall.

name: Bookout
description: Aim for and pass through the 15-foot long open book that is about 15 feet left of the blocky innermost corner. Coldshuts are at the top of this corner.

name: Cobbled Corner
description: Cobbled Corner climbs the blocky, innermost corner of the large left-facing dihedral avoiding the offwidth sections.

name: The Lechuguilla Lizard
description: Ascends the ramp past Crossover, past the unnamed 5.11, and then up the steep, blocky features.

name: Miter Cuts
description: Climb the slab.

name: The Mooty One
description: Ascends the ramp past Crossover (right of) and continues up the steep, blocky features.

name: North American Pre-Clovis
description: Short, fun route ascends the left face of the sheltered alcove and steps right at the top.

name: Offset Roof
description: Offset Roof uses a line about 30 feet left of the Cobbled Corner and may or may not pass through the open book.  At about 145 feet undercling the horizontal roof crack left to a vertical, thin crack on a green lichen face. The chain anchors are about 20 feet above the roof edge.

name: President's Ride
description: Climbs the right side of the Slab. Some of the bolts were placed to protect both an easy option and a more difficult way.

name: Punch Line
description: Two 90-foot pitches lead to the SW corner of the Upper Ramp. Aim for two angle iron hangers that are visible at 35 feet up, then trend left to a ledge with coldshut anchors. The second pitch wanders to the SW corner of the Upper Ramp, but has one bolt at its crux.

name: Ramset
description: Climbs the left side of the slab to the right of the large wide crack.

name: Side-Slip
description: Climb the slabby face to the right facing dihedral.

name: The Zachoff
description: P1-11a, 90', 10 bolts: Climb along the slabby flakes, which gradually steepen, to reach a small right-facing dihedral/overhang. Step and palm left to the anchors. Rappel or climb less continuous second pitch.   P2-10c, ~110', bolted: Move left on the ledge and climb the short, steep headwall to gain the easier ramp above and continue to coldshuts.

name: *Laramie Talk Show
description: Mind the gap, then climb straight up the thin, slabby, splitter crack. If your lucky, play-by-play commentator Dingus McGee will be there to cheer you on.

name: Alvin
description: Alvin climbs the broken crack system. There are good small/medium gear placements around the short sections of the crack that get wide.

name: Bergland's Crack
description: Climbs the steep, offset hands splitter crack, which becomes a double crack system near the top.

name: Captain America's Slab
description: Break out your sticky rubber and hold on. The climb traverses left across the steepening slab.

name: Carter Goes to Haiti
description: Follow the thin crack system up the slabby face.

name: Coercive Utopians
description: Climb the slab of the left-facing open dihedral.

name: Devil's Interval
description: Climb the left-angling crack and face features left of the large left-facing dihedral. Begins 10' left of the dihedral, stepping left at the bolt to gain the left-angling crack.

name: Dielectric Power
description: Climb the obvious, wide splitter crack.

name: Low Handcrack
description: Handcrack.

name: Montreal Steak Seasoning
description: Montreal Steak Seasoning climbs the outside of the Tunnel Boulder.   P1-9+, 80', ~10 bolts: Chimney to the outside of the Tunnel Boulder, step on, highstep the overlap, and continue up the arete to anchor.   P2-7, 80', mostly gear and few bolts: Step across gap and follow the slabby crack system to anchor.

name: Nixon Goes to China
description: Climbs the open corner crack system.

name: Sauerkraut Shakedown
description: Crack.

name: Scream Traverse
description: Climb the large left facing dihederal traversing left below the large roof.

name: Walk Like an Egyptian
description: Route climbs the slabs and the flake system directly below The Sphinx.   P1, 10b, 80': Follow the arete of the detached boulder, and slab up to the benched belay.   P2, 10a, 80': Continue up the short arete or dihedral, step right and follow the hand cracks to the wide flake.   An alternate pitch 1 uses gear on the crack system to the right (10a) to reach the benched belay.

name: Woofer
description: Climbs the steep finger to hand splitter crack. Unlike Vedauwoo, tape is not required.

name: Black Fusion
description: On North Face of Sherard Tower

name: Boom or Bust
description: Climbs left side of Sherard Tower

name: Continuation
description: Right of Crystal Blue Persuasion

name: Crystal Blue Persuasion
description: So don't you give up now ... so easy to find ... just look to your soul ... and open your mind.    Crystal Blue Persuasion generally traverses the slab and overlaps from right to left crossing the bottom of the large, black water streak.    P1:140',10c- Steps left past the large overlap and arcs to the comfy belay ledge.   P2:70',8- Up the short dihedral and pad left.   P3:80',10a- Follow thin, flared crack, step over the short overlap, and surmount the improbable corner roof crack above.   P4:80',10a- Zig zag right, back left, then up. Keep an eye out for the blue crystals on the last pitch.

name: Swallows Race
description: P1-10+, 115', 10 bolts.   P2-10+, 40', 1 bolt and gear. Reachy traverse pitch.   P3-11b/c, 110', bolts gear.   P4-7, 80', gear.   Alternate P4 finishes on steep bolted face on left, 11c.

name: Direct Northeast
description: The beautiful remote setting, mind blowing exposure, and fantastic climbing will make this a memorable adventure. The climbing consists of mostly hand and finger crack through several roofs with many edges for face/foot holds.  The Laramie Range guidebook mentions the route can be done in 2 pitches, however we did in 3 to avoid rope drag.    Pitch 1 (5.6)    Probably a couple of ways to start this, all of which are no harder than 5.6 and will lead to a low angle right facing corner that gradually becomes steeper. We stopped and belayed approximately 5-feet below the first roof.    Pitch 2 (5.9)    Crux pitch! Climb through the first roof (mostly hands with great feet). There is a pinched chock stone (that thing isn't coming out but it is thin) at the end of the roof that acts as a jug. Climb nice fingers to the next roof and pull through it. The next section only takes small (0.4 C4 and smaller and offsets are nice) gear and it takes a little thinking to place but it is there. This section is a little balancy and for me was the crux. Enter the overhanging chimney with a finger and hand crack in the back. A #5 Camalot was nice towards the top of the chimney. Do some awkward exposed moves and we belayed approximately 5-feet below the great roof.    Pitch 3 (5.8) The Great Roof    This thing looks like it will be 5.12 from the start of the climb but it is mostly hands and there are really good feet the whole way making most of the climbing 5.7 with a few 5.8 moves. The exposure is AWESOME here! Turning the roof isn't bad. Follow a 5.6 hand crack to the top of the formation.    Decent    There are 3 sets of rap anchors on the northeast side. They aren't super easy to find but they all consist of 2-bolts with a rap ring through each bolt and they are painted beige. You will basically be rappelling 30-feet to the left (as you face the climb) of the route.

name: Bag of Tricks
description: Fun 3-pitch moderate trad route with solid rock, bolted anchors and good position.  This isn't my route, but Matt was kind enough to point it out. P1 starts on a wide sloping ledge w anchor bolts about 25' off the ground. It goes up a broken crack and traverses right to the obvious crack with anchor bolts above a tree, ~130'. P2 is a hand/fist crack to another ledge w anchors, 90'. P3 steps right around the corner and follows the crack through 2 roofs to the top where there are more anchors, 135'.  This crack widens to a #4, but the angle drops off so I didn't use one.  Wind, flakes and length makes a rap' from the top of the route unadvisable. We walked west and down one tier, then traversed back east on an airy ramp to the rings at the top of P2. Then down to the P1 rings above the tree; then straight down 115' to a ledge where we could scramble down. (I suppose you could walk up to the anchors for the Northeast Shoulder route and do 3 raps.)  Matt told us to go down 2 tiers and traverse over to a different set of rap anchors and proceed straight down to the start of the route.  He has plans to streamline this in the future.

name: Ancient History
description: Ancient History was the route chosen BITD or at least attempted?  One rusted army ring angle piton was in the short crack down low.  The modernized sport route follows this short crack and continues up the slab until one can walk without using the hands.

name: Belgium Chocolate Waltz
description: The Belgium Chocolate Waltz is a climb here that makes use of the irregularities from what would be on a slab route.  Yes, its a pleasing zig zagging line the make use of the various small brownish corners and holds.

name: Corner Groveling
description: Corner Groveling is a steepish slab climb that makes use of the left side of the dihederal when the edges get to small for peddling your feet.

name: Fox Trot
description: Last route west on the "Visor Wall." (It's only about 15 feet further west to the next "Tarzan Wall" route.)  Anyhow, this route is old style, but with beefy pro; the first 2 hangers look like big pound-ins, the next 5 are homemade angle iron hangers with 3/8" bolts. (If you have way beefy 'biners, they may not fit easily through the holes.)  P1 zigzags for about 95 feet to cold shuts.  I'm sure most folks rap off here.    If you do the second pitch, a light rack may help, but not much.  There's another angle-iron bolt hanger and a bent piton on the way to running out the entire 70m along moderate terrain.  We walked maybe 40 feet west on the ledge to the top of Moorcroft City Slicker and did 4 raps down w 1 rope.

name: Foxy Dance
description: Foxy Dance is a sustained micro edge crimper climb without rests but good pro.

name: Irish Spring
description: Thinning moves to the roof (Visor) and a heck of a step up balance move to get over it to the chains.

name: Master Plan
description: Another fun face route with a lot of texture.  Collect the whole set.

name: Moorcroft City Slicker
description: Aside from one move getting over the roof on pitch 1, this is a nice 5.4-5.6 slab wander.  Take a couple pieces for second pitch if you want - we didn't use them.  Anchors are all bolted.P1 - Up towards the left weakness in the roof band.  Or, up a bit right of this on "Red Line" if that looks more fun.  There are two bolted anchors 5 feet apart just above this roofline... pick one.P2, P3 - Up.  Just go basically up on some nice mellow slab.  Start of pitch 2 you might want some gear (otherwise P2 only has 1 bolt), and you should have a right facing corner of semi broken rock just to your left.P4 - gets real low angle here.  But... up and slight right and you will find another bolted anchor.We linked 1 and 2, and 3 and 4 with a 60m.Descent - rap the route.

name: Photon Torpedo
description: Climbs over the same visor roof the other routes do, but easier and just plain fun with big holds over the roof.

name: Prime Directive
description: Clip a couple bolts trending right from the ledge, then up some overlaps past a couple more clips.  Finish on some featured face.

name: Radical Bastard
description: Short.  Two clips past some lieback/pull left edge, zig zag right then left and reach up to the anchors.

name: Sugar Crack
description: Short, but mostly fun.  Start up some easy slab (past a couple bolts).  Make the hardest move at ~15feet to get over a small step/roof and into a nice hand crack.  Follow this crack up on gear, then climb on top of some block up top to the bolted anchors.

name: Tarzan
description: Climb some blocks and fight a small tree - then delicate stepping up and right with a little overlap for help.  Eventually head straight up on easier slab.  Make a neat mantle at the roof and find some bolted anchors in front of you.

name: Tasty Waves
description: Basically the same as Dennis's Corner Groveling, but stick to the crack with gear and stop at the bolted anchor before heading out horizontal roof up top.A large pod you can fit in, followed by being forced out of the crack, and some nice hands/thin hands to finish before stepping out to the anchors.Single rack.  We placed a 5 and it was fine, but would have rather had a 6.

name: Voodoo Cherry Bomb
description: There's some pretty thin, sketchy balance moves up on that ramp, just below the roof.

name: 10 Men With Regular Jobs
description: Mixed bag - some nice hands, some more facey stuff, a thin crack up higher.  Varied climbing mostly in a left facing corner.  Build a gear anchor up top and the walk off.

name: Thin Mint
description: Wide crack with some hands in the back, up to a short but clean and fun finger crack crux.  Exit the finger crack and continue up a more broken system to the top.  Belay on gear and walk off.
Fun technical warm up. hard for 5.7. Especially for gym climbers.
Just right of the 5.9
Fun slabs right of Three Amigos and left of the giant tree.

name: Al Roker's Dead
description: The Laramie Range book calls this the New World Order Wall. Lots of moderate sport routes here, wish I'd done more. True to the name, it gets toasty in the sun.  The book calls this 5.7, but it's easier than the climb to the right.  See what you think.

name: Ambien Daydream
description: This is the left start variation of the route Intolerant of the Intolerant (5.10b).  Climb up and right along the left side of a thin black section of rock for 2 bolts to join the other route.  Move up through easy rock to the bottom of a left facing corner. Layback through a brief but strenuous section followed by another short crack before the anchors.

name: Baja Koolaid
description: Short bouldery crux off a ledge leads to fun easy 5.11 face climbing.

name: Baja Runner
description: This fun link up creates the likely highest quality line on the Golden Panel: Start up Baja Koolaid and do that crux, move left past the obvious link-up-bolt (drilled but not added yet) into the top of the super difficult Blade Runner climb avoiding its V9 crux. Go to the top in the usual fashion. May be 12c, will adjust grade(s) based on community consensus.

name: Blade Runner
description: This is the amazing line just right of "Bon Bini" that tackles a super tough v10 facey boulder followed by immaculate easy 5.12 face and then a slab outro that will blow your mind. Original and challenging, this line is a stunner and the current hardest addition to the LRR.

name: Bon Bini
description: This route is just right of center on the clean vertical face on the right side of Toaster Wall.  It ascends a blocky ledge system down low and then follows edges and seams up the vertical face to the anchors.  A defined crux comes between bolts 4 and 5 as you conquer the bulge.

name: Crispy Cougar
description: Bouldery start leads to a couple balancy sections separated by good rests. Meander up abstruse sequences to earn the pumpy technical crux at the last bolt to the anchors. Dig deep on decent crimps with meh feet to clip the chains or take the big, safe ride! Must do for the astute puzzle lover.

name: Currently Dreaming
description: Start up a mini-triangular slab just right of Frankenpoodle and lift-the-car-off-the-baby with a burly V7 intro boulder to great jugs. Then climb 5.11 until able to stem to the top of the Frankenpood for a great and exposed rest. From here there is a 5.11 runout (a bolt hole is drilled and a bolt needs to be added). Then encounter another burly crux before sweet finger locks and a cool top out onto the lunch ledge. Sit down, take your shoes off and enjoy the view for however long before tackling the final 12a headwall. Super fun climbing the whole way! You will feel like you are "currently dreaming" your way up this immaculate climb.

name: Frankenpoodle
description: Engaging juggy climbing in the crack system down low leads to a long move out to a shelf on the face and then another long move to the resting jug. Get it back here for a final challenge up the block and an exciting pull-over onto the slab above.

name: Gleaming the Cube
description: Start up the lower arete with a nice crack for the left hand. Move up and out right under the roof with difficult climbing. Follow the bolts up and a bit right to a grovel top out.

name: Hell or Highwater
description: This stellar addition is immediately left of "Gleaming the Cube". Tackle broken high-quality rock up easy 5.10 to a roof and tackle a hard boulder problem to mount a simple perch and clip the anchors. Subtract or add a star and give yourself 12a-12c for using the left wall or the chimney. The route is still enjoyable to climb this way, but is a completely different experience. Definitely an unusual but thoroughly enjoyable climb.

name: Intolerant of the Intolerant
description: Fantastic warm-up to the left of the Project wall, climb a cool easy boulder problem to a slab and alpine feeling buggy corner. Exit a bulgy flared crack up high to gain the anchors. The left stat var. of this is "Ambient Daydream" and connects into this line after a couple bolts and a harder intro boulder.

name: Lippy Dyke 5.11a
description: This stiff little number climbs a prominent dark water streak.  Steep, pumpy climbing with a final crux below the anchors.  Listed as 5.9+ in Zack's guidebook...take that with a large grain of salt.

name: New World Order
description: Another nicely bolted moderate slab in the sun.  Collect the whole set!   The book calls it 5.7, and it is harder (IMHO) than Al.  What do you think?

name: Pandemic
description: This is the wonderful swirly stone route just left of Lippy Dyke that was begging to be bolted and climbed. Start down and right of the first bolt on a big jug rail and work up and left, past two bolts to a recondite crux and keep traversing left on sublime climbing; mostly tech slopers and pinches. hanging the draws is a bit scary from left of the bolts, and is much easier if you climb above the bolts a tad. spooky falls, although unlikely, would result in a bit of a pendjy. There has been some discussion about relocating bolts 4 to the top 8"-12" to the left for easier, less scary position and clipping. The FA'ist is fine with this. Sustained and technical, this route is AMAZING! Can set up a TR or hang bolts from "Social Distancing".

name: PROJECT B
description: Very Cool project. These will get done soon. Start from a stepped-up bloc with your belayer below. Climb right-facing side pulls (body facing East) through a series of cruxey liebacks to gain a marginal rest. Cool underclings and big pulls guard easier runout climbing above. Shares anchors with Project A.

name: Puzzler
description: Very hard, slopey, technical face and slab climbing, this aptly named beast will test your problem solving ability to the max. Extremely positional with very cool holds and sequences, this recondite masterpiece is as cerebral as it is subtle. Good conditions certainly help, but this line is definitely one of the prizes of the crag despite its unassuming and perhaps even uninteresting initial appearance from the ground. Good luck!

name: Sex Machine
description: This may be the best 12d in the Laramie River Range. Maybe Wyoming. A short 5.11 intro gains a face-arete bouldery v6 crux. Then share the no-hands from "GTC". Then embark on wild roof climbing to an amazing juggy quartz dyke! This last roof is 12a-c depending on height, but not a game-changer. Finish up amazing outro moves on perfect rock. Get on up!

name: Social Distancing
description: This long route will deposit you on top of the Toaster formation but needs a bit of work. The current anchors only allow a lead with an 80 meter rope or with a lot of shenanigans, experience and a 70 meter. It would do well with a midway anchor if anyone is so inclined. Basically two very cool 5.11c's stacked into one mega pitch. fun!

name: The Sybian
description: Get on and ride - it’s guaranteed to please! Short but stout climbing through two roof systems. Mount up on the big undercling on the left side of the roof systems to the left of Pandemic above the east slab routes. Pull over onto the slab where the holds suddenly thin out and pad your way up to the base of the 2nd roof. Engaging and powerful climbing leads to an interesting roof mount terminating in a unique chickenhead jug and pull-over onto the slab above.

name: Three Amigos
description: Start by climbing 30 feet of easy 5.9 bolted wide buggy crack to gain an interesting footwork dependent crux to transition to the left arete. Airy and delicate moves deliver you to the slopey topout exit moves and the chains. There was/is a huge Raven's nest in the roof just left of this line visible by peering around left from the anchors.

name: Yoshi-Meister
description: Fun climb up a big sweep of rock.  I'm always impressed at the varied nature of 5.8s and this one is no exception. The first pitch is the exciting part, set your anchors as high as you'd like after the steep stuff, ~90'. P2, a comfortable hand/fist off-angle pitch that ran an entire 70m all the way to where the crack peters out near the top.  I then wandered around unroped to find the beige rap anchors (up right) for 3 raps down off double ring anchors that lands about 70 feet right of the start.  A little more adventurous than the regular clip-ups.

name: A Child of Destiny
description: HighBalla!

name: Cherokee DiveBomb
description: Roof, Tough pull is all i got to say, didn't trust myself to get this before the season ended... somewhat height dependent.

name: Manic Hysteria
description: Beautiful rock and texture... I won't describe this one. Try it!

name: Avoiding the Stix
description: This route was done before Coins to cross the Stix but has the same great start and moves on the overhanging almost corner like face/bulge but about half way up exits left but not enough to use the large crack for finishing.

name: Coins to Cross the Stix
description: Some stemming will get you onto the overhanging bulge that has big holds and long reaches. The last portion of the climb crosses into the territory of coin sized holds and is more at arete climbing.

name: Gordian Knot
description: An overhanging small crimp face just above ground level when properly traversed rightward leads to a more obvious line of holds above.

name: Gravitas
description: A somewhat overhanging gully-like emergence of 2 angled faces that may appear more like a crack climb but the somewhat undetectable holds when viewing the route form the ground make for a difficult onsight.

name: Ungrateful Reach
description: Proceed up a series of ledges that look unlikely to have an easy connecting line to a shallow right facing corner.  Finish using some holds to right and then back left.

name: A Stellar for Seller
description: This very long pitch makes use of the Main Tower's longest face by beginning near the lowest point on the SW corner.  After a steeper start than the rest of face the route moves to the easiest turf at each option.

name: Cornering the Start
description: Moderate face above the corner start leads to some shallow groves and holds near a corner with no bite on top of them.  You'll feel you can just walk off to the left on the smallish ledge on the left.  Do it without any holds?

name: Makeshift Rodeo
description: On this sport route just bounce up through some roofs and rightward on bigger holds.

name: Obstructing Just Neiss
description: a steep start leads to cul de sac of bulges to choose from and once out the going gets easier.  On the left this pitch joins route to left.

name: Woody Deck?
description: This route passes near the west end of the upper south face but near this corner the usable hold cease in the upward path and must be taken up to the right.  The needed clip is not so easy on this traverse.

name: Hardesto
description: A steep crimpy face with the appearance of having several doable ways.

name: Late Arrival
description: Some big hold and ledges on this steep face will make for a rest while using the climb as a warm up if you just had breakfast at dusk.

name: Rook Movement
description: Another steep long line on good rock with some required moves

name: Steep with Options
description: a superb steep face with a mostly definite line but some closeouts that will need negotiating.

name: Squaw Rock
description: There are several crack systems that could be use to get you to the spire's summit.    Bob Scarpelli reports that a guide covering this area was published. Maybe this was it: A Climber's Guide to Southeastern Wyoming. J. Halfpenny. Self-Published, 1972. I have not seen a copy, but maybe there is one at Coe Library, UW under lock and key.

name: Death Wish
description: The Crux is right in the middle of the climb.  The best part of this climb is the start.  Their are no foot holds at all.  What you think is rock in the first 4 feet is really solid looking sand.  You have to depend on the crack at first.  The bad part is their was few holds that you cant trust but fun climb regardless.  I would climb this again for sure!!!

name: All The Aces
description: Starts steep on the giant hoop jug and punches up and right through sidepulls and crimps. Gets really juggy after the second bolt.

name: Bang to Rights
description: Get to the jug handle after a big move from the ground.  Layback the crack then head to the right following great pockets that end to soon.  Thin mantle and tip toes get you to the anchors.

name: Born to Lose
description: Bolted face to the right of the Iron Horse crack.  Follow rails, crimp and pockets up to its common anchor with Iron Horse

name: The Claw
description: Follows pockets and big sidepulls left of the bolts, crosses back to the right through small ledges, then moves up again on pockets and sidepulls to the right of the bolts. Finishes with an awkward roof pull.

name: Dirty Love
description: Crack on the back side of the right most tooth, opposite side from Iron Horse.

name: Heart of Stone
description: Basically 3 boulder problems stacked following the seam. You get a good rest before the 3rd problem. Bottom is techy and powerful. Top problem is the crux,  involving an undercling mono and some wild jamming.

name: Iron Horse
description: Zig zag your way up to the roof and pull it (crux). Follow the leaning crack to the top.

name: Love Me Like A Reptile
description: Starts with a long reach to a rail then hits crimps up the bottom steep slab to a hueco finish.   Crux is between bolts 1 and 2

name: Stay Clean
description: Short and steep climbing through big, juggy moves to a thin finish.

name: Stone Dead Forever
description: Beautiful seam above the "Les Lives" graffiti. Route name inspired by the artist.    This is an incredible route,  get on it.   Juggy moves lead to an undercling sequence to a rest followed by a boulder move to a finishing jug.  A fun rope swing can be set up on this route if you bring some long slings for the top anchor

name: Tear Ya Down
description: A steep start leads to easier, but delicate climbing to anchor.  Look for the shell fossils in the rock at the bottom.

name: Prairie Arete
description: Just a taste of what Needle Peak has to offer. Please use the free PDF guide to gain info on the area. Link provided in the Needle Peak main page.     The arete! Start on the low end of the arete on slopers.

name: Best of the 80's
description: Fun jam/lieback problem.

name: Brosuf
description: Extra fun boulder problem. Good features, basically every kind feature you can imagine. But negative holds makes this problem a bitch.

name: Dry Cooler
description: Decent V5 problem, foot placement along the bottom of the route is tricky.

name: Hold The Pad Dad
description: An awesome splitter boulder problem. The picture doesn't show the crack, but its pretty obvious.

name: Parental Control
description: Nothing too hard, just be sure to pay attention to footing.

name: Memories and Dust
description: Crux is hitting high slopey hold. All holds on route are good. Follow the crack and use the arete if you'd like.

name: Lynguistics
description: Pretty thin problem. Although it is a total classic. There's a balancy move about halfway up that's tough to get around.

name: Hail was Hell
description: Sit start on medium sized ledges for both hands and toe into small crystals. Move to slopers and crimpers with thin top outs

name: Pumpy's Traverse
description: This a long pumpy traverse starting right and moving left. There is a sit start in the progress which might make this V5or maybe V6

name: Sunset Crack
description: Hand/foot jam and undercling moving up more rightward onto thin crimps and sharp chickenheads/nubs. Top out on a mantle.

name: The Two Moose
description: Start in crack, jamming and undercling.  Move left in the horizontal crack. Move up on crimps before hitting the arete. I dont think this variation has been done by any one before me. If so let me know

name: Coyotes
description: This moves up on small balancing crimps and a long pull to small bubs at the topout.  Start feet in a large wave. Hands are on small edges

name: Move on Right
description: Start is same as Coyotes but instead ofmoving up, travel right on thin edges with hard feet a top out just left of the main face

name: Up the face
description: Move up the main north face. Start on crimpsand move up to ledges that grow bigger leaving you to a secure top out

name: Apogee Project
description: N/A

name: Half Moon Arete
description: Ultra classic problem. Starts on the east face. Obvious line.

name: Sunset Screamer
description: Awesome slightly overhanging granite rock that is super solid. Final move is a throw to a block pinch, pretty sweet. Great landing.

name: Abrasion Dyno
description: Crux is obviously getting to jug.

name: August Party
description: Crux is getting onto the crack from start.

name: My Opinion Is 3 Cents
description: A reachy, crimpy problem. Foot placement is tricky.

name: Pabst Relapse
description: Great problem! Fun moves on a small hold.

name: Project- Far Left
description: There is a definite line, but moves are incredibly difficult and straining. I haven't had time to really project it, but I'm sure the whole project is very sustained.

name: Yoddle
description: A great crack that runs the whole face with great yet painful locks to a huge jug.

name: First in Flight
description: Start with a left hand in the obvious crack and your right hand in a pocket. Feet are obvious as well.

name: Baby Breen
description: Follow a series of sidepulls and rails to the top.  Can be topped out directly, or on the rail higher and to the right for more excitement.

name: Corporate Secrets
description: Start on a good left hand edge and right hand crimp.  Pull up on another good right crimp and reach for a left hand sidepull.  Up and over from there.

name: Fateful Findings
description: Techy moves, awesome features, and a perfect landing make this an instant classic!  This is easily the best line in the area so far and one of Pinedale's finest.Start on two opposing smeary thumb catches in the center of the big face and make a balancy move to gain the good undercling.  Float over to the rail and follow it to the top!

name: Government Secrets
description: Start in the same seam that is used on "It's a Magical Day!" but on the right side, using it like a lieback.  Make a move or two up and right to gain the big shelf.  Mantle onto it, then top out straight up.

name: It's a Magical Day!
description: Great for the grade.  Follow a right hand crack and crystally left hand features up the South corner of the boulder.

name: Laptop Massacre
description: Short, but packs a punch; crush this one like a laptop under a heavy book.  Start as low as you can on the obvious rail and make some tense moves to gain the big sidepull, then go straight up the face.

name: Buy a Better Stickbrush
description: Make a cruxy lieback move or two up to some big jugs, then stand up to a good finish on smaller holds.

name: Fill In the Blank
description: Bolted slab route following double water grooves and ending on a ledge with a 2 bolt rap anchor. edging down low leads to delicate friction above. Fun, but still needs a little traffic!

name: Bens Birthday Suite
description: This route goes up to the roof and traverses under to the right for about 20 ft. Then pull the roof with safe protection and proceed on slabs to the top

name: Deceitful Business
description: An easy low angle first pitch brings you to the money pitch, which combines an early overhang with some nice slab moves above it to the anchors.

name: Donkey Day
description: A mellow route with a thought-provoking crux about halfway up the first pitch.

name: The Lost Stopper
description: Pitch 1: Climb to anchors 60 ft up or get to the natural belay at a good ledge 80 ft up.   Pitch 2: Take the direct up not following the swoop to the right. Climb a steep section where a bolt protects, then follow the crack up that leads left.

name: The Lounge Lizard
description: Pitch 1: Climb to the anchors or the natural belay just as you would for lost stopper.   Pitch 2:  Climb through a steep section with a bolt that protects. Follow a Right facing dihedral to the top

name: Mr. Friction
description: This route can either be done in one pitch with a 60m rope or it can be done in two pitches to reduce rope drag going over the apex. If you break it in two there is anchors set at the apex.

name: A Walk in the Park
description: Slab climbing leads to a roof, which can be climbed directly (Call It What You Want) or bypassed, here, to the right by a crack system.  Plentiful features are available for hands and feet.

name: Addicted to Crack
description: Start by leading up a steep section with bolts. It will flattern out and gradually grow into steeper slabs. Get to the Left facing dihedral where there is good protection. follow to a good belay ledge at the top.

name: Call It What You Want
description: A variation on A Walk in the Park that goes through the roof after the third bolt via a layback in a crack through the roof.

name: Crankin
description: Follow a ledge system that runs into a roof with a large crack running vertical. Pull the interesting roof with good pro placements and follow fun slabs to the ridge. follow ridge up right to a safe belay station.

name: Front & Center
description: Climb a right facing corner for about 15 feet, then move onto the face, eventually finishing the route in a left facing corner.

name: Journey Around the Sun
description: Slab climbing leads to a roof and the first crux.  The second, more difficult crux, involves a bulge after the roof.  It's easy going after passing the bulge.

name: Sure Fire
description: A variation of Front & Center that follows a bolt-protected direct line for the second half of the route.

name: Caught your moss
description: Follow the crack that has a couple trees in it. There is a big tree in a flat belay area. No bolts or chains yet. Top rope or belay from a tree above.

name: Dick Around Left
description: Crux is towards the top on a balancy crossover move.

name: Dick Around Right
description: Crux may vary.

name: Project- North Side
description: I haven't had much time to try to climb this but is considerably hard! Very high boulder problem, very exposed and slightly overhung.

name: Re-Birth
description: The crux is towards the top. I love this problem. You are working up a face that is enclosed by another. Very very cool!

name: Traverse
description: Start on the north side of the boulder on a small arete and move left. Go all the way around the rock encountering some tricky positions

name: Burning in the Rocks
description: Start on the left where the rock dives under itself. The start is akward but once established the rest goes well.  Move right on small nubs and top out. Short 2 move problem

name: Embares"me"ing
description: Start on the south face on small crimps and edgy feet. Make hards moves up and right onto smaller features.

name: Trad line
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: P.D.W. (Pretty Damn Western)
description: A wild line on deteriorating rock.  The crux is the third pitch,  traverse right on grassy cracks to a ledge with a wild 7/8 foot wide rectangular break in the rock with a crack on the left side. Overcome the #5 overhanging crack on the left side of a chimney/ wide cut out of the rock with enticing exposure, then into a roof with wild stemming on the edge of the chimney feature and good locks up one crack then at the roof reach high and right and switch to and to a hand crack that cuts upwards and thins down to a #.1 sem which leads into a blank moderate face on somewhat crumbly rock onto a foot ledge and then the very top of the corner where without climbing the corner you walk on to the upper ledge and build an anchor save a BD #4 and some finger-sized gear for the anchor.    P1 To get to the base of the money pitch Follow the ramp to a roof with a finger crack in it to the left of the corner about 60M 5.3 P2 Move up about 50 feet over the roof and follow the grassy crack to the base of the corner belay there with BD #1, #2, or, #3  sized gear. 5.9 P3 Next traverse right on grassy cracks to the base of the chimney feature and hold on to your reins because its about to get Pretty Damn Western!!  DECENT walk/ or short rope left to tree and rap off a cord with a non-locker, if still there or leave your own stuff, down to a gully their rap of a fallen tree that is jammed on top of a live tree no cord. 70 M rope is nice but probably not necessary F.A. was with 64 M rope but nothing was a rope stretcher

name: Hitting Props
description: Start on TOP of the rock, lowering ourself from good jugs. The further down you go the thinner it gets so pick your line.  Make thin moves left until you ca pull up jugs to top out. Ranges from V2-V6

name: 6-Iron
description: The off-width crack in the middle of the boulder next to the boulder, not the huge choss corner but the mellow very wide one on the side with Skunk Cabbage.

name: Skunk Cabbage
description: Follow up the good cack on the left side tell it stops, step left and place some gear in the suspect flake and enter the crux, (IT IS ALSO THE RUNOUT PART) balance up and over onto the slab. Not the best route but pretty fun if your tooling around the lake during the summer!

name: I and I
description: Foot placement makes this route hard. Couple overhand moves up high that are tricky. Good flat landing for tons of pads. All holds are solid except top has some gravel and sand from when a huge piece broke on me. I'll have to clean off better. Hopefully the wind and rain has taken care of it for me.

name: Trial and Tribulation
description: Start on big jug, set a heel hook, and mantle over bulge onto slopey top. Be careful here.

name: Green Traveler
description: Crux is feet placement and some crappy finger locks.

name: Let's Go For A Quicky
description: Artistic moving problem that requires some static moves.

name: Slappa Da Bass
description: Slopers and crimps. Give it a nice little slap as you make your way to the top.

name: Spotlight
description: Tricky because of the polished rock. Some slopey holds make progression a little difficult.

name: A Good Variety
description: Start on the northeast side of the boulder on small crimps and shallow feet. Move left to small shelfs, slopers, heal hooks, and follow crimpers that get smaller,  Big dynamic move from a small crimper to sharp (be carefull) edge, barn door action occurs and move up the arete on balancing moves. Hence the name a good variety! FUN PROBLEM

name: Press Blocks
description: This problem is a very hard complex problem, i have never seen problems or moves like this.  Start on the left most series of "blocks" which are obvious that protrude from the rock. Heel hook and press to the next block getting into a horizontal and pressurous position. Make a hard move to get on small balancing crimpers and top out going up a golden dyke. Good Luck

name: B n' C
description: Reachy feet but other than that a cool prob. The starting flake is flexing a little bit but you can manage the problem without it.

name: Summer Snow Storm
description: Pretty good problem...I like it a lot anyways. I first climbed it in a blizzard during June. The problem is on the south face where I am at (in the blue coat).

name: Undecided
description: This is one of the coolest V0's I know. There are like 3 or 4 jugs all the way up the problem.

name: Looking For Blindness
description: Crux is hitting a slopey/high hold from the arete. Kinda creepy move but you'll be good.

name: Warm Up
description: Just a simple warm up to get the going a little bit.

name: While The Bitches Are Away
description: The only thing I'm worried about on this problem is a big hollow sounding hold. It will probably fall off soon so take caution when climbing it. Pretty good problem with a lieback sit start.

name: Independent Learning
description: Fun arete climb on the South Tower. Beginning holds hard to get comfortable with. Foot placement is tricky as well. I gave a PG-13 rating because once you get higher on the problem you could fall backwards onto the backside of the North Tower, so be careful.

name: Stem-ulatation
